# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bleacher-report
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **1990 FIFA World Cup** was the 14th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was held from 8 June to 8 July 1990 in Italy, the second country to host the event for a second time (after Mexico in 1986).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams representing 116 national football associations entered and qualification began in April 1988.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twenty-two teams qualified from this process, along with the host nation Italy and defending champions Argentina.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament was won by West Germany, for the third time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat defending champions Argentina 1–0 at the Stadio Olimpico in Rome, a rematch of the previous final four years earlier.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy finished third and England fourth, after both lost their semi-finals in penalty shootouts.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica, Ireland and the United Arab Emirates made their first appearances in the finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for a FIFA World Cup finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon went on an unexpectedly strong run in the tournament, becoming the first African team to reach the quarter-finals of the World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The official match ball was the Adidas Etrusco Unico.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup is widely regarded as one of the poorest World Cups in terms of the games.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It generated an average 2.21 goals per game – a record low that still stands – and a then-record 16 red cards, including the first dismissal in a final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, the tournament had a significant lasting influence on the game as a whole.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In England, the team's success in this tournament led to the resurgence of the domestic top-flight, which had suffered from violence on the pitch and hooliganism by spectators throughout the 1980s.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It saw the introduction of the pre-match Fair Play Flag (then inscribed with "Fair Play Please") to encourage fair play.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Overly defensive tactics of many teams led to the introduction of the back-pass rule in 1992 and three points for a win instead of two, both of which have encouraged attacking play, increasing spectator interest in the sport.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup stands as one of the most watched events in television history, garnering an estimated 26.69 billion non-unique viewers over the course of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the first World Cup officially recorded and transmitted in HDTV, which was a joint effort of the Italian broadcaster RAI and Japan's NHK.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The huge success of the broadcasting model also had a lasting impact on the sport.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] At the time, it was the most watched World Cup in history in non-unique viewers, later bettered only by the 1994 and the 2002 editions of the competition.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The vote to choose the hosts of the 1990 tournament was held on 19 May 1984 in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Here, the FIFA Executive Committee chose Italy ahead of the only rival bid, the USSR, by 11 votes to 5.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This awarding made Italy only the second nation to host two World Cup tournaments after Mexico had also achieved this with their 1986 staging, having agreed to replace Colombia as hosts the year before the 1990 hosts were chosen.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy had previously held the event in 1934, where they had won their first championship.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, England, France, Greece, West Germany and Yugoslavia also submitted initial applications for the 31 July 1983 deadline.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A month later, only England, Greece, Italy and the Soviet Union remained in the hunt after the other contenders all withdrew.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] All four bids were assessed by FIFA in late 1983, with the final decision over-running into 1984 due to the volume of paperwork involved.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In early 1984, England and Greece also withdrew, leading to a two-horse race in the final vote.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet boycott of the 1984 Olympic Games, announced on the eve of the World Cup decision, was speculated to have been a major factor behind Italy winning the vote so decisively, although this was denied by the FIFA President João Havelange.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet state media responded by accusing FIFA of political corruption, and blamed the organisation's American sponsors (chiefly Coca-Cola) for influencing the decision.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Iran also planned to host the competition.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They proposed it to FIFA in 1977, but a few months later they withdrew their request.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 116 teams entered the 1990 World Cup, including Italy as host nation and Argentina as reigning World Cup champions, who were both granted automatic qualification.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thus, the remaining 22 finals places were divided among the continental confederations, with 114 initially entering the qualification competition.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to rejected entries and withdrawals, 103 teams eventually participated in the qualifying stages.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thirteen places were contested by UEFA teams (Europe), two by CONMEBOL teams (South America), two by CAF teams (Africa), two by AFC teams (Asia), and two by CONCACAF teams (North and Central America and Caribbean).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The remaining place was decided by a play-off between a CONMEBOL team and a team from the OFC (Oceania).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After finishing in third place in 1986, France missed the tournament for the first time since the 1974 edition.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Mexico was disqualified during the qualification process for fielding four overage players in a prior youth tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three teams made their debuts; this was the first World Cup to feature Costa Rica, the Republic of Ireland, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, Cameroon, Czechoslovakia and Yugoslavia also returned after missing the 1986 tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for the World Cup finals and the last time Mexico did not participate in the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twelve stadiums in twelve cities were selected to host matches at the 1990 World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Stadio San Nicola in Bari and Turin's Stadio delle Alpi were completely new venues opened for the World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Of the twelve stadiums used, only four (San Siro, Luigi Ferraris, Comunale of Florence, and Renato Dall'Ara) had been used for the 1934 FIFA World Cup, while Trieste was the only host city from 1934 not to be selected for the 1990 tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ten existing venues all underwent extensive programmes of improvements in preparation for the tournament, forcing many of the club tenants of the stadia to move to temporary homes.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Additional seating and roofs were added to most stadia, with further redevelopments seeing running tracks removed and new pitches laid.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to structural constraints, several of the existing stadia had to be virtually rebuilt to implement the changes required.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Like España '82 and México '86, the group stage of this tournament was organised so an individual group only played in two cities in close proximity to each other.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group A only played in Rome and Florence (hosts Italy played all but two competitive matches in Rome: their semi-final match was played in Napoli, and their match for third place in Bari), Group B played their matches in Naples and Bari (except for Argentina vs.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon, which was the opening match of the tournament, played in Milan), Group C played their matches in Turin and Genoa, Group D played all their matches in Milan and Bologna, Group E played only in Udine and Verona, and Group F played in the insular cities of Cagliari and Palermo.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The cities that hosted the most World Cup matches were the two biggest cities in Italy: Rome and Milan, each hosting six matches, and Bari, Naples, and Turin each hosted five matches.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cagliari, Udine and Palermo were the only cities of the 12 selected that did not host any knockout round matches.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The England national team, at the British government's request, played all 3 of their group stage matches in Cagliari on the island of Sardinia.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hooliganism, rife in English football in the 1980s had spilled over onto the European continent when 39 mostly Italian Juventus supporters were killed and 600 were injured at the 1985 European Cup Final in Brussels while trying to flee from an attack by Liverpool supporters.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Italian authorities' presence proved to be justified as there were several riots during the time England were playing their matches in Cagliari, leading to a number of injuries, arrests and even deportations.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of the construction cost in excess of their original estimates and total costs ended up being over £550 million (approximately $935 million).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rome's Stadio Olimpico which hosted the final was the most expensive project overall, while Udine's Stadio Friuli, the newest of the existing stadia (opened 14 years prior), cost the least to redevelop.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Squads for the 1990 World Cup consisted of 22 players, as for the previous tournament in 1986.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Replacement of injured players was permitted during the tournament at FIFA's discretion.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two goalkeepers – Argentina's Ángel Comizzo and England's Dave Beasant – entered their respective squads during the tournament to replace injured players (Nery Pumpido and David Seaman).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 41 match officials from 34 countries were assigned to the tournament to serve as referees and assistant referees.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Officials in italics were only used as assistants during the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Referees dressed only in traditional black jerseys for the final time at a World Cup (a red change shirt was used for two Group C games in which Scotland wore their navy blue shirts).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The six seeded teams for the 1990 tournament were announced on 7 December 1989, two days ahead of the draw.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Organising Committee also decided ahead of the draw, to allocate the six seeded teams into the first position of the six groups, in the alphabetic order of their seeding rank: first seed to Group A, second seed to Group B, etc.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seeds were decided by FIFA, primarily based on the nations' ranked position in the 1986 World Cup (counting double), with the ranked position in the 1982 World Cup also considered as a secondary influence (counting normal).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Six of the final eight in 1986 had qualified for the 1990 tournament, the missing nations being Mexico (quarter-final in 1986) and France (third place).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy did not reach the final eight in 1986, but despite this were still seeded first in 1990 as hosts.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In total, the primary seeding criteria hereby resulted in seven countries to be potentially seeded.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As the tournament structure only had place for the selection of six seeded teams, this left FIFA needing to exclude one of the six teams qualifying for a seed based on the primary sporting criteria.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA first decided, that all qualified teams having played the 1986 semi-finals (Argentina, Germany, Belgium), should be guaranteed a seeding place behind the first seeded host nation Italy.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Consequently, one of the three qualified nations who were eliminated in the 1986 quarter-finals (Brazil, England or Spain), should not be seeded based on the secondary sporting criteria - looking at their 1982 FIFA World Cup results.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Owing to their performance in 1982, but also to their overall World Cup record, Brazil were seeded third, and not considered to drop out of the seedings.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA therefore had to choose if England or Spain should be granted the last seeding slot, and ultimately opted to seed England ahead of Spain.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain had only been eliminated in their 1986 quarter-final on penalties, albeit by fourth-placed Belgium, while England had been defeated in their 1986 quarter-final after 90 minutes by eventual winners Argentina.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If the only criteria had been the 1986 ranking, then Spain should have been seeded as #6 instead of England; a viewpoint being supported by FIFA President João Havelange as late as 29 November 1989.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If taking the 1982 ranking into consideration, England however had performed slightly better than Spain - as they had finished ahead of them in Group B of the second group stage.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If only considering the results of the 1978 event, it could on the other hand have been counter argued, that Spain by their group stage performance and Netherlands by their silver medal accomplishment, should have been seeded rather than England and Belgium who both had failed to qualify.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spanish officials believed the seeding was contrived to ensure England would be placed in Group F, the group to be held off the Italian mainland, in a bid to contain England's hooliganism problems.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their coach Luis Suárez said, "We feel we've been cheated...they wanted to seed England and to send it to Cagliari at all costs.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA countered that "the formula was based on the teams' respective showings during the previous two World Cups.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This is in no way a concession to English hooliganism".
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, this argument was countered by the fact that Netherlands had themselves failed to qualify for both the 1982 and 1986 World Cups, which was considered the most important factor in the decision not to seed them.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the group stage had been completed, England could be said to have justified their seeded position by winning their Group F ahead of Ireland and Netherlands; while Spain seemed to have made their own point about being worth a seeded position, by defeating Belgium to top their own Group E.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 9 December 1989, the draw was conducted at the Palazzo dello Sport in Rome, where the teams were drawn out from the three pots to be placed with the seeded teams in their predetermined groups, in alphabetic order.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A special draw decided teams should first be drawn from Pot 1, then from Pot 3, and finally from Pot 2.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each drawn team also had their group position number drawn from a separate group bowl, in order to decide their exact match schedule.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The only stipulation of the draw was that no group could feature two South American teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The procedure for the draw, was presented by FIFA at a press meeting the day before the draw.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, after having received objections from Italian officials, FIFA opted to slightly change their special Pot 2 rule, during the last 24 hours ahead of the draw.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] When FIFA accepted to change the Pot 2 rule into the final version presented at the televised draw, this lowered the chance for the Italian Group A to draw a South American Pot 2 team, from the 80% chance created by the initial wording to only a 33% chance (two out of six teams).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was hosted by Italian television presenter Pippo Baudo, with Italian actress Sophia Loren and opera singer Luciano Pavarotti conducting the draw alongside FIFA general secretary Sepp Blatter.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The event also featured the official mascot of this World Cup, *Ciao*, a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolour body that formed the word "ITALIA" when deconstructed and reconstructed.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In each group, the teams would play three matches, one against each of the other teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Victories would be granted 2 points, while a draw awarded 1 point.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After completion of the group stage, the best two teams of each group as well as the four best ranked third places, advanced to round 16 in the knockout stage.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This format was identical with the tournament structure being used in 1986.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A total of 52 games would be played, including the final and a match for third place between the two semi-final losers.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament generated a record low goals-per-game average and a then-record of 16 red cards were handed out.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the knockout stage, many teams played defensively for 120 minutes, with the intention of trying their luck in the penalty shoot-out, rather than risk going forward.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two exceptions were the eventual champions West Germany and hosts Italy, the only teams to win three of their four knockout matches in normal time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were four penalty shoot-outs, a record equalled with the 2006, 2014, and 2018 tournaments, until it was surpassed by the 2022 tournament, with five.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Eight matches went to extra time, also a record tied with the 2014 tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Losing finalists Argentina were prime examples of this trend of cautious defensive play, choosing to do so because 3 of their best players were left off the squad due to injury.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They scored only five goals in the entire tournament (a record low for a finalist).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina also became the first team to advance twice on penalty shoot-outs and the first team to fail to score and have a player sent off in a World Cup final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Largely as a result of this trend IFAB introduced the back-pass rule in time for the 1994 tournament to make it harder for teams to time-waste by repeatedly passing the ball back for their goalkeepers to pick up.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three, rather than two points would be awarded for victories at future tournaments to help further encourage attacking play.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon reached the quarter-finals, where they were narrowly defeated by England.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They opened the tournament with a shock victory over reigning champions Argentina, before topping the group ahead of them, Romania and European Championship runners-up the Soviet Union.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was fired by the goals of Roger Milla, a 38-year-old forward who came out of international retirement to join the national squad at the last moment after a personal request from Cameroonian President Paul Biya.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Milla's four goals and flamboyant goal celebrations made him one of the tournament's biggest stars as well as taking Cameroon to the last eight.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of Cameroon's squad was made up of players who played in France's premier football league, Ligue 1 - French is one of the officially spoken languages in Cameroon, it being a former French territory.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In reaching this stage, they had gone further than any African nation had managed in a World Cup before; a feat not surpassed until Morocco reached the semi-final in 2022.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's feat (equalled by Senegal in 2002 and Ghana in 2010) remains the best by a Sub-Saharan African team.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was African football's biggest yet on the world stage and FIFA subsequently decided to allocate the CAF qualifying zone an additional place for the next World Cup tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite the performances of nations such as Cameroon, Colombia, Ireland, Romania and Costa Rica, the semi-finalists consisted of Argentina, England, Italy and West Germany, all previous World Cup winners, with eight previous titles between them.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the 1970 tournament, this is only the second time in the history of the World Cup this has occurred.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams which finished first, second and third had also contested both the two previous World Cup Finals between themselves.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Group stage saw the twenty-four teams divided into six groups of four teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each group was a round-robin of six games, in which each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were awarded two points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams coming first and second in each group qualified for the Round of 16.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The four best third-placed teams would also advance to the next stage.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As was typical of a World Cup staged in Europe, the matches all started at either 5:00 or 9:00 in the evening; this allowed for the games to avoid being played in the heat of an Italian summer, which would soar past 86F (30C) all over Italy.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hosts Italy won Group A with a 100 percent record.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat Austria 1–0 thanks to substitute Salvatore 'Totò' Schillaci, who had played only one international before but would become a star during the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A second 1–0 victory followed against a United States team already thumped 5–1 by Czechoslovakia.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Czechoslovaks ended runners-up in the group, while the USA's first appearance in a World Cup Finals since 1950 ended with three consecutive defeats.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon defeated world champions Argentina 1–0.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite ending the match with only nine men, the African team held on for a shock 1–0 win, with contrasting fortunes for the Biyik brothers: François Omam-Biyik scoring the winning goal with a downward header, shortly after seeing André Kana-Biyik sent off for a serious foul.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's second red card was awarded to Benjamin Massing for up-ending Caniggia in the last few minutes as Argentina pressed for an equalizer.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Cameroon's second game, the introduction of Roger Milla was the catalyst for a 2–1 win over Romania, Milla scoring twice from the bench (making him the oldest goalscorer in the tournament).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] With progression assured, Cameroon slumped to a 4–0 defeat in their final group game to the Soviet Union (in what would be their last World Cup due to the dissolution of the Soviet Union), who were striving to stay in the tournament on goal difference after successive 2–0 defeats.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina lost their veteran goalkeeper, Nery Pumpido, to a broken leg during their victory over the USSR: his replacement, Sergio Goycochea, proved to be one of the stars of their tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final match, a 1–1 draw between Romania and Argentina sent both through, equal on points and on goal difference but with Romania having the advantage on goals scored; Romania were thus second, and Argentina qualified as one of the best third-placed teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica beat Scotland 1–0 in their first match, lost 1–0 to Brazil in their second, then saw off Sweden 2–1 to claim a place in the second round.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil took maximum points from the group.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They began with a 2–1 win over Sweden, then beat both Costa Rica and Scotland 1–0.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Scotland's 2–1 win over Sweden was not enough to save them from an early return home as one of the two lowest-ranked third-placed teams.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group D featured the most goals of all the groups, most due to two large wins of West Germany and defensive inadequacies of a United Arab Emirates team that lost 2–0 to Colombia, 5–1 to West Germany and 4–1 to Yugoslavia.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The West Germans topped the group after a 4–1 opening victory over group runners-up Yugoslavia.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of Group E were Spain, for whom Míchel hit a hat-trick as they beat South Korea 3–1 in an unbeaten group campaign.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Belgium won their first two games against South Korea and Uruguay to ensure their progress; Uruguay's advance to the second round came with an injury-time winner against South Korea to edge them through as the weakest of the third-placed sides to remain in the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group F featured the Netherlands, England, the Republic of Ireland and Egypt.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the six group games, no team managed to score more than once in a match.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England beat Egypt 1–0—the only match with a decisive result—and that was enough to win the group.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England took the lead with an early goal for Lineker against Ireland, but Sheedy's late equaliser secured a draw.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands drew with Egypt: they had taken a 1–0 lead, but Egypt equalised with a penalty by Abdelghani.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England then drew 0–0 with the Netherlands; a goal from a free-kick by Pearce was disallowed.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] For the second World Cup in succession, however, England lost their captain Bryan Robson to an injury which put him out of the tournament, just over halfway through their second match.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Ireland missed a number of scoring opportunities in the second half of the other 0–0 draw against Egypt.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the first four matches all four teams had equal records with two draws, one goal for and one goal against.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both teams qualified, but they had to draw lots to place the teams in second and third place.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored; 4) Drawing of lots (if deciding qualification).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The knockout stage involved the 16 teams that qualified from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were four rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The successive rounds were: round of 16, quarter-finals, semi-finals and the final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Scores after extra time are indicated by (a.e.t.) and penalty shoot-outs are indicated by (pen.).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Two of the ties—Brazil vs Argentina and Italy vs Uruguay—pitted former champion countries against each other and West Germany met the Netherlands in a rematch of the 1974 World Cup Final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The all-South American game was won for Argentina by a goal from Claudio Caniggia with 10 minutes remaining after a run through the Brazilian defence by Diego Maradona and a strong performance from their goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It would later come to light that Branco had been offered water spiked with tranquillisers by Maradona and Ricardo Giusti during half time, to slow him down in the second half.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Initially discredited by the press, Branco would be publicly proven right years later, when Maradona confessed the episode on a TV show in Argentina.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Hosts Italy beat Uruguay 2–0, thanks to goals from Schillaci and Aldo Serena.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match between West Germany and the Netherlands was held in Milan, and both sides featured players from the two Milanese clubs (Germans Andreas Brehme, Lothar Matthäus and Jürgen Klinsmann for Internazionale, and Dutchmen Marco van Basten, Ruud Gullit and Frank Rijkaard for Milan).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After 22 minutes Rudi Völler and Rijkaard were both dismissed after a number of incidents between the two players, including Rijkaard spitting on Völler.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] As the players walked off the pitch together, Rijkaard spat on Völler a second time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Early in the second half, Jürgen Klinsmann put the West Germans ahead and Andreas Brehme added a second with eight minutes left.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A Ronald Koeman penalty for the Netherlands in the 89th minute narrowed the score to 2–1 but the Germans saw the game out to gain some revenge for their exit to the Dutch in the previous European Championship.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Colombia, Roger Milla was introduced as a second-half substitute with the game goalless, eventually breaking the deadlock midway in extra time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Three minutes later he netted a second after Colombian goalkeeper, René Higuita was dispossessed by Milla while well out of his goal, leaving the striker free to slot the ball into the empty net.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Though the deficit was soon reduced to 2–1, Cameroon held on to become the first African team to reach the World Cup quarter-finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Costa Rica were beaten 4–1 by Czechoslovakia, for whom Tomáš Skuhravý scored the tournament's second and final hat-trick.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's match with Romania remained goalless after extra time and the Irish side won 5–4 on penalties.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] David O'Leary converted the penalty that clinched Ireland's place in the quarter-finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Ireland thus became the first team since Sweden in 1938 to reach the last eight in a World Cup finals tournament without winning a match outright.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Yugoslavia beat Spain 2–1 after extra time, with Dragan Stojković scoring both the Yugoslavs' goals.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were the final qualifier against Belgium, as midfielder David Platt's swivelling volley broke the stalemate with the game moments away from a penalty shoot-out.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first game of the last 8 saw Argentina and a Yugoslav side, reduced to 10 men after only half an hour, play out a goalless stalemate.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The holders reached the semi-finals after winning the penalty shoot-out 3–2, despite Maradona having his penalty saved.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A second Argentine miss (by Pedro Troglio) looked to have eliminated them until goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea – playing because first choice Nery Pumpido broke his leg during the group stage – rescued his side by stopping the Yugoslavs' final two spotkicks.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's World Cup run was brought to an end by a single goal from Schillaci in the first half of their quarter-final with hosts Italy, thus becoming the team who advanced the furthest in a World Cup without winning a single match.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West Germany beat Czechoslovakia with a 25th minute Lothar Matthäus penalty.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The quarter-final between England and Cameroon was the only quarter-final to produce more than one goal.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Despite Cameroon's heroics earlier in the tournament, David Platt put England ahead in the 25th minute.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the second half, the game was turned on its head during a five-minute stretch: first Cameroon were awarded a penalty from which Emmanuel Kunde scored the equaliser; then in the 65th minute Eugene Ekeke put Cameroon ahead.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Cameroon came within eight minutes of reaching the semi-finals before they conceded a penalty, which Gary Lineker converted.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Midway through extra time, England were awarded another penalty and Lineker again scored from the spot.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were through to the semi-finals for the first time since 1966.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first semi-final featured the host nation, Italy, and the world champions, Argentina in Naples.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] 'Toto' Schillaci scored yet again to put Italy ahead in the 17th minute, but Claudio Caniggia equalised midway through the second half, breaking Walter Zenga's clean sheet streak throughout the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were no more goals in the 90 minutes or in extra time despite Maradona (who played for Naples in Serie A at the time) showing glimpses of magic, but there was a sending-off: Ricardo Giusti of Argentina was shown the red card in the 13th minute of extra time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina went through on penalties, winning the shoot-out 4–3 after more heroics from Goycochea.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The semi-final between West Germany and England at Juventus' home stadium in Turin was goalless at half-time.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Then, in the 60th minute, a free-kick tapped to Andreas Brehme resulted in a shot which was deflected off Paul Parker into his own net.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England equalised with ten minutes left; Gary Lineker was the scorer, Parker somewhat redeeming himself by providing the assist.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Klinsmann was guilty of two glaring misses and both sides struck a post.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had another Platt goal disallowed for offside.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match went to penalties, and West Germany went on to win the shoot-out 4–3, Pearce having his penalty saved and Waddle firing over the bar.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The two matches had the exact same score at 1–1, an identical penalty shootout score at 4–3, and the same order of penalties scored.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The game saw three goals in a 15-minute spell near the end of the match.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Roberto Baggio opened the scoring after a mistake by England's goalkeeper Peter Shilton, in his final game before international retirement, presented a simple opportunity.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A header by David Platt levelled the game 10 minutes later but Schillaci was fouled in the penalty area five minutes later, leading to a penalty.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Schillaci himself got up to convert the kick to win him the tournament's Golden Boot for his six-goal tally.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Nicola Berti had a goal ruled out minutes later, but the hosts claimed third place.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had the consolation prize of the Fair Play award, having received no red cards and the lowest average number of yellows per match.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The final between West Germany and Argentina has been cited as one of two most cynical and lowest-quality of all World Cup Finals, next to the 2010, between Spain and Netherlands.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the 65th minute, Argentina's Pedro Monzon – himself only recently on as a substitute – was sent off for a foul on Jürgen Klinsmann.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Monzon was the first player sent off in a World Cup Final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina, weakened by suspension and injury, offered little attacking threat throughout a contest dominated by the West Germans, who struggled to create many clear goalscoring opportunities.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The only goal of the contest arrived in the 85th minute when Mexican referee Edgardo Codesal awarded a penalty to West Germany, after a foul on Rudi Völler by Roberto Sensini leading to Argentinian protests.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] An earlier possible foul by Goycoecha, who tripped Klaus Augenthaler in the box, had not been given.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] German commentators speculated, that the subsequent penalty was therefore a concession by the referee.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Andreas Brehme converted the spot kick to settle the contest.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the closing moments, Argentina were reduced to nine after Gustavo Dezotti, who had already been given a yellow card earlier in the match, received a red card when he hauled Jürgen Kohler to the ground during a stoppage in play.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 1–0 scoreline provided another first: Argentina were the first team to fail to score in a World Cup Final.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] With its third title (and three second-place finishes) West Germany – in its final tournament before national reunification – became the most successful World Cup nation at the time along with Italy and Brazil (who had also won three titles each then).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West German manager Franz Beckenbauer became the first man to both captain (in 1974) and manage a World Cup winning team, and only the second man (after Mário Zagallo of Brazil) to win the World Cup as a player and as team manager.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was also the first time a team from UEFA won the final against a non-European team.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Salvatore Schillaci received the Golden Boot award for scoring six goals in the World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] This made him the second Italian footballer to have this honour, after Paolo Rossi won the award in 1982.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, 115 goals were scored by 75 players (none credited as own goals).
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA published the first All-Star Team in 1938, but it never made an All-Star Team again until 1990 due to ensuing complaints.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In 1990 an All-Star Team was announced in combination with the Golden Ball ceremony.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was chosen by the same journalists who chose the best player, but this team is still considered unofficial.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After the tournament, FIFA published a ranking of all teams that competed in the 1990 World Cup finals based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 1990 FIFA World Cup are divided into two categories: FIFA World Cup Sponsors and Italy Supporters.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot of this World Cup was "Ciao", a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolore body.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Etrusco Unico", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:bleacher-report/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official song of this World Cup was "Un'estate italiana".
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] The **1991 Pan American Games**, officially known as the **XI Pan American Games** (Spanish: *XI Juegos Panamericanos*) and commonly known as **Havana 1991** (Spanish: *La Habana 1991*), were held in Havana, Cuba from 2 to 18 August 1991.
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] There were 4,519 athletes from 39 countries of the PASO community, with events in 33 different sports.
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] The main stadium was the Estadio Panamericano, a multi-use stadium in Havana that holds 50,000 people.
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] Havana was the only non-withdrawn bid to host the **1991 Pan American Games**.
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] At the Pan American Games (ODEPA) Assembly, from November 12 to 14, 1986, in Bridgetown, Barbados, Mar del Plata withdrew its bid, leaving Havana as the winner to host the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] London, Ontario, Canada also submitted a bid, but withdrew from the bid process due to the federal government prohibiting all funding from any international multi-sport events (aside from the 1988 Calgary Winter Olympics).
[src:bleacher-report/1991-pan-american-games] The 1991 Games' mascot named *Tocopan*, was a combination of the country's national bird "Tocororo" and the first three letters of Panamerican.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The **1992 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XVI Olympic Winter Games** (French: *XVIes Jeux Olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Albertville '92** (Arpitan: *Arbèrtvile '92*), were a winter multi-sport event held from 8 to 23 February 1992 in and around Albertville, France.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Albertville won the bid to host the Winter Olympics in 1986, beating Sofia, Falun, Lillehammer, Cortina d'Ampezzo, Anchorage, and Berchtesgaden.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Winter Olympics were the last winter games held in the same year as the Summer Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The next Winter Olympics were held two years after this one instead of the usual four, which allowed the Olympic Games to take place on every even-numbered year instead of every four years.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The Games were the fifth Olympic Games held in France and the country's third Winter Olympics, after the 1924 Winter Games in Chamonix and the 1968 Winter Games in Grenoble.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] This games was the first of two consecutive Olympic games to be held in Western Europe, preceding the 1992 Summer Olympics in Barcelona, Spain.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] 18 events in Figure skating, short track speed skating, speed skating, and the opening and closing ceremonies took place in Albertville.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 39 other events were held in the nearby 9 villages and resorts around Savoie: Courchevel, La Plagne, Les Arcs, Les Menuires, Les Saisies, Méribel, Pralognan-la-Vanoise, Tignes, and Val d'Isère.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Sixty-four National Olympic Committees and 1,801 athletes participated in six sports and fifty-seven events.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] This included both the Unified Team, representing the non-Baltic former Soviet republics, and Germany, newly consolidated again as a team following the reunification of the former East and West Germany in 1990.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The event also saw the debut of eight nations in the Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The Winter Olympic program has grown this time with the addition of 11 new events.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] These were the last Winter Olympics to include demonstration sports, consisting of curling, aerials and ski ballet, and speed skiing.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Due to a rule change implemented in 1986, this was the last edition in the history of the Winter Olympic Games in which all speed skating events were held in an open-air venue.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] A record-breaking seven locations bid for the games.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The non-winning bids were from Anchorage, Berchtesgaden, Cortina d'Ampezzo, Falun, Lillehammer, and Sofia.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 91st IOC Session, held in Lausanne on 17 October 1986, voted Albertville the host of the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Bjørn Dæhlie and Vegard Ulvang dominated the men's cross-country skiing races, both taking home three gold medals with Norway taking a medal sweep in the event.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] 16-year-old Ski jumper Toni Nieminen became the youngest male gold medalist in a Winter Olympic event until 2002.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Petra Kronberger won both the combined event and the slalom of alpine skiing, while Bonnie Blair won both the 500 m and 1000 m speed skating events, and Gunda Niemann took both of the longest races.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Annelise Coberger from New Zealand became the first Oceanian athlete to win a medal in women's alpine skiing slalom, making her the first athlete from the southern hemisphere to mount the podium at the Winter Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Swiss speed skier Nicolas Bochatay died on the penultimate day of the Games, when he crashed into a snow-grooming vehicle during a training run.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Olympic Winter Games marked the last time both the Winter and Summer games were held in the same year.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Winter Olympics also marked the last time France hosted the Olympics until 2024, when Paris became the second city to host the Summer Olympics three times.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] France is set to host the Winter Games in 2030 in the French Alps, 38 years after Albertville played host and will host it again in 2030.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Winter Games mascot, Magique (Magic), was a small imp in the shape of a star and a cube.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The mascot was created by Philippe Mairesse and replaced the bid mascot, which was a mountain goat.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The star shape symbolized dreams and imagination, while the mascot's red and blue colors originated from the French flag.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] There were 57 events contested in 6 sports (12 disciplines).
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] This was the last time demonstration events were included in the Winter Olympics program.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Of the 8 events that were under evaluation, 4 received the endorsement to be included in an official form in future editions of the Games (Curling tournaments and the aerials events on the freestyle skiing).
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The other four events (speed skiing and skiing ballet events on the freestyle skiing) were rejected and have not since returned.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Sixty-four nations sent competitors to the 1992 Olympics, including seven nations making their first appearance at a Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Following the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, six former-Soviet bloc nations chose to form a Unified Team, while the Baltic states of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania competed as independent nations for the first time since 1936.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Czechoslovakia made its last appearance in the Winter Olympics before its dissolution at the end of 1992.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] United Nations Security Council Resolution 757 took effect on 30 May 1992 (97 days after the closing ceremonies), and Yugoslav athletes were able to participate under their country's national symbols.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] It also suspended the activities of the Yugoslav Olympic Committee, making the country's athletes ineligible to compete on the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Despite this, some of their athletes classified in individual sports and gained authorization to compete as Independent Olympic Participants (which also happened at the 1992 Summer Paralympics).
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Yugoslav athletes returned to the Olympic Games in the 1996 Summer Olympics, when only Serbia, Montenegro and Kosovo were still part of the country.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Winter Olympics were the first time since the 1964 Summer Olympics that Germany competed with a unified team.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] Through the 2022 Winter Olympics, this has been the only participation of Swaziland (now Eswatini) and Honduras in an edition of the Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1992-winter-olympics] The 1992 Games are the last in which the speed skating venue was outdoors.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Having lost the bid for the 1992 Winter Olympics to Albertville in France, Lillehammer was awarded the 1994 Winter Games on 15 September 1988, two days before the 1988 Summer Olympics opening ceremonies at the 94th IOC Session in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Due to the calendar changes made in 1986, this was the only time that the Winter Olympics took place two years after the previous Winter Games, and the first to be held in a different year from the Summer Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This was the first Winter Olympics that took place in a year with the Asian Games, Commonwealth Games, and FIFA World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This was the second Olympic Games of any type hosted in Norway — the first being the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo — and the fourth Olympics overall to be held in a Nordic country, after the 1912 Summer Olympics in Stockholm, Sweden, and the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki, Finland.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer is the northernmost city ever to host the Olympic Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Sixty-seven National Olympic Committees and 1,737 athletes participated in six sports and sixty-one events.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Fourteen countries made their Olympic debuts, of which nine were former Soviet republics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Games also saw the introduction of stricter and more rigid qualifying rules, reducing the number of under-performing participants.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Six new events were introduced into the Olympic programme: new distances in short-track speed skating and aerials, and speed skating events were held indoors.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Almost two million people spectated at the Games, which were the first to have the Olympic Truce in effect.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Olympics were followed by the 1994 Winter Paralympics from 10 to 19 March.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Manuela Di Centa and Lyubov Yegorova dominated women's cross-country skiing, taking five and four medals for Italy and Russia respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] A crowd of more than 100,000 saw Italy beat Norway by 0.4 seconds in the men's 4 × 10 km relay.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Vreni Schneider won a complete set of medals for Switzerland in Alpine skiing, while Norway took a podium sweep in the men's combined competition.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In ladies' singles figure skating, 16-year-old Ukrainian Oksana Baiul won gold, narrowly defeating Nancy Kerrigan, who won silver; this was the first Ukrainian medal at the Olympics in their first independent appearance.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Johann Olav Koss won three speed skating golds for Norway, while 13-year-old Kim Yun-mi from South Korea became the youngest-ever Olympic gold medalist.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Sweden defeated Canada in a dramatic penalty shootout in the ice hockey final.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Russia topped the medal table, winning 11 gold medals, while Norway collected the highest number of medals overall, with 26.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The event also gained notoriety for the assault of Nancy Kerrigan.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The idea for an Olympic bid for Norway was born in 1981, when Falun in neighbouring Sweden was defeated by Calgary in Canada to host the 1988 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Along with the Norwegian government, the bid was also publicly encouraged and supported by the Swedish government, largely to help stimulate the economy of their inland counties.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer originally bid for the 1992 Games but came fourth in the voting, with the Games ultimately awarded to Albertville, France.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In 1986, at the 91st IOC Session in Lausanne, the IOC announced the intent to separate the Summer and Winter editions (which had been held in the same year since the inception of the Winter Olympics in 1924) after the 1992 Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The two editions of the Olympics have since alternated every two years during the four-year cycle.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer subsequently launched another bid, now for the 1994 Games, with some drastic modifications of the project, such as a new indoor speed skating venue and an additional ice hall in Lillehammer.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Supplementary government guarantees and funds were secured for the new bid.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Three other locations put in bids for the 1994 Games: Anchorage (United States), Östersund (Sweden), and Sofia (Bulgaria).
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer was elected to host the 1994 Winter Games at the 94th IOC Session, held in Seoul on 15 September 1988, two days before the start of the 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The overall responsibility for the games was held by the Lillehammer Olympic Organizing Committee, which was created on 14 November 1988 and led by Gerhard Heiberg.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Between 1989 and 1993, the committee was reorganized several times with various subsidiaries.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] On 11 February 1993, it became a joint venture owned 51% by Lillehammer Municipality (as main stakeholder), 24.5% by the Government of Norway, and 24.5% by the Norwegian Olympic Committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This model was also used for the Lillehammer Paralympic Organizing Committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Norwegian government had issued a guarantee for the Games and also covered the expenses related to infrastructure.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The total cost of the Games was 7.4 billion Norwegian krone (NOK), of which NOK 0.95 billion was expended by the ministries, NOK 4.48 billion was for operations and event expenses, and NOK 1.67 billion was for investments.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Games had a revenue of NOK 2.71 billion, of which NOK 1.43 billion was from television rights, NOK 0.65 billion was from sponsors, and NOK 0.15 billion was from ticket sales.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Production and execution of the broadcasting, which cost NOK 462 million, was a joint venture of the Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation (NRK), the CTV (Canada) (CTV), and the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) (the NRK is part of the collaboration of EBU members).
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] NRK and EBU had 1,424 people working at the Olympics, while international broadcasters sent an additional 4,050 accredited broadcasting personnel.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The transmission rights for the games were held by EBU in Europe, CBS in the United States, NHK in Japan, CTV in Canada, the Asia-Pacific Broadcasting Union, Nine Network in Australia, as well as other broadcasters in other countries.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The total transmission rights price was 350 million United States dollars, 310 million of which were paid only by CBS.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This value was attributed in part to the Harding–Kerrigan affair.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] As of 2010, the viewership in the United States was still the highest ever for the Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] NOK 460 million was used on information technology, with the main system running on an IBM AS/400.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] 3,500 media terminals were in use during the games based on the Info '94 system; it was the first Winter Olympics to have terminals installed abroad.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Seiko delivered the time-keeping devices.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Telecommunications were delivered by Telenor, including signal transmission.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This included a mobile radio network with nine base stations.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] There were 61 events contested in 6 sports (12 disciplines).
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] As the 1988 Winter Games, the Organizing Committee decided not to build a specific Olympic Stadium for the opening and closing ceremonies and opted to conduct them at the ski jumping hill, Lysgårdsbakken.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Artistic content presented a range of Norwegian and Nordic cultures, including elements such as Sami joik, Telemark skiing, fiddlers and folk dancing, simulations of Norwegian traditional events, such as wedding processions, and the figure of vetter from Norse mythology.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After speeches by Heiberg and IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch, the Games were officially declared opened by King Harald V. and the Olympic Anthem was performed by the lyrical singer, Sissel Kyrkjebø.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After, the Olympic Flame was to be carried down the ski jump before lighting the cauldron.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Originally this task had rested upon Ole Gunnar Fidjestøl, but after he broke an arm in a practice jump, his back-up, Stein Gruben, received the honor.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The cauldron was lit by Crown Prince Haakon Magnus.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Olympic oaths were taken by Vegard Ulvang for the athletes and Kari Kåring for the officials.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Since the 1992 Games, the rules for combined changed, where the winner was determined by total time instead of points.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The women's downhill was originally scheduled for Hafjell, but after protests due to the hill difficulties it was moved to Kvitfjell, which also hosted the men's downhill and super-G.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the men's events, Germany's Markus Wasmeier won two disciplines, giant slalom and super-G, finishing ahead of the United States's Tommy Moe on the super-G.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Moe won the downhill ahead of Norway's Kjetil André Aamodt, who came in third in the super-G.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Austria's Thomas Stangassinger won the slalom ahead of Italy's Alberto Tomba.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the combined, Norway took a medal sweep, with Lasse Kjus winning ahead of Aamodt and Harald Christian Strand Nilsen.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the women's events, Switzerland's Vreni Schneider was the most successful, winning the slalom, taking silver in combined and taking bronze in giant slalom.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The only other athlete to take multiple medals was Italy's Isolde Kostner, who took a third place in both downhill and super-G.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The downhill was won by Germany's Katja Seizinger, super-G by the United States' Diann Roffe, the giant slalom by Italy's Deborah Compagnoni, and the combined by Sweden's Pernilla Wiberg.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Russia and Germany split all the individual men's medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the 10 km sprint, Russia's Sergei Tchepikov won ahead of Ricco Groß, both with a clean sheet.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Bronze winner Sergei Tarasov won the 20 km individual ahead of Germany's Frank Luck and Sven Fischer.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Germany easily revenged itself by winning the 4 × 7.5 km relay ahead of Russia and France.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the women's class, Canada's Myriam Bédard won both the individual events, finishing ahead of Belarus' Svetlana Paramygina on the 7.5 km sprint and ahead of France's Anne Briand on the 15 km individual.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the 4 × 7.5 km relay, the format since 1992 was changed from three to four participants.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Russia, with a clean sheet, won ahead of Germany, who made six misses, with France taking the bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In two-man, Switzerland took the top two places, with Gustav Weder, Donat Acklin winning 0.05 seconds ahead of Reto Götschi and Guido Acklin, who were again 0.15 seconds ahead of Italy's Günther Huber and Stefano Ticci placing third.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In four-man, Germany-II, consisting of Harald Czudaj, Karsten Brannasch, Olaf Hampel and Alexander Szelig, finished 0.06 seconds ahead of Switzerland-I and 0.23 ahead of Germany-I.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Participants from five countries took all the medals of the ten events.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Starting in 1994, the Olympics alternated which of the medium-distance and long-distance races had classical and freestyle. men's 4 × 10 km relay was watched by a crowd of nearly 150,000.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Norway, Italy and Finland followed each other tightly for three and a half rounds, with the second and third exchange of the three talking place within 1.1 seconds of each other.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Finland fell behind in the end, and Norwegian Bjørn Dæhlie and Italian Silvio Fauner battled to the end, with Italy beating Norway by 0.4 seconds.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Dæhlie won the 10 km classical and 15 km freestyle pursuit, while taking silver in the 30 km freestyle.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Kazakhstan's Vladimir Smirnov won the 50 km classical, in addition to silver in the 10 km and the 15 km.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Norway's Thomas Alsgaard won the 30 km, while Finland's Mika Myllylä took an individual silver and a bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Italy's Manuela Di Centa and Russia's Lyubov Yegorova dominated the women's events.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] They took five and four medals each, respectively, and between them winning all the races.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Yegorova finished ahead of Di Centa on the 5 km classical and the 10 km pursuit, while Di Centa finished ahead of Yegorova on the 15 km freestyle, and also won the 30 km classical ahead of Norway's Marit Wold.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Finland's Marja-Liisa Kirvesniemi took two bronze medals, in 5 km and 30 km.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the 4 × 5 km relay, Norway and Russia kept up with each other until the final stage, in which Anita Moen lost to Yegorova, with Italy finishing third.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] With Yegorova's sixth career gold, she was tied as the most-winning Winter Olympic participant.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] On 6 January, Tonya Harding's ex-husband, Jeff Gillooly and his friend Shawn Eckardt, conspired with Shane Stant to club fellow female figure skater Nancy Kerrigan in the knee.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Both Harding and Kerrigan were selected for the Olympic team.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After Harding admitted to helping to cover up the attack, the United States Olympic Committee initiated proceedings to remove her from the Olympic team, but Harding retained her place after threatening legal action.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the ladies' singles, Ukraine's Oksana Baiul narrowly won ahead of Kerrigan and Chen Lu, with Harding finishing eighth.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the men's singles, Russia's Alexei Urmanov won ahead of Canada's Elvis Stojko and France's Philippe Candeloro.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Relaxation of the rules led to several former stars returning, such as ice dancing 1984 Champions Great Britain's Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean, who took a bronze behind Russians Oksana Grishuk and Evgeny Platov, and Maya Usova and Alexander Zhulin.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In pair skating, the Russians also took a double, with Ekaterina Gordeeva and Sergei Grinkov winning ahead of Natalia Mishkutenok and Artur Dmitriev.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Aerials was added as a discipline, after it had been a demonstration sport at the previous two games.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Ski ballet, which had been a demonstration sport in 1992, was dropped.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Canada dominated the men's events, with Jean-Luc Brassard winning the men's moguls ahead of Russian Sergey Shupletsov.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the men's aerials, Switzerlands's Andreas Schönbächler won ahead of Canada's Philippe LaRoche and Lloyd Langlois, with Canadians also claiming the fourth and sixth places.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the women's disciplines, Norway was the only nation to take two medals; Stine Lise Hattestad won the moguls ahead of the United States' Liz McIntyre.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the aerials, Lina Cheryazova won, claiming Uzbekistan's only medal, ahead of Sweden's Marie Lindgren and Norway's Hilde Synnøve Lid.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Twelve teams participated in the ice hockey tournament, divided into two groups.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Each played as a single round robin, with the four best advancing to the single elimination medal tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Group A saw Finland win all five matches, while the host nation lost all theirs.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Also Germany, the Czech Republic and Russia advanced from the group, all with three victories.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Group B was won by Slovakia ahead of Canada, Sweden and the United States.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The quarter-finals saw the Czech Republic, the United States, Germany and Slovakia eliminated.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the semi-finals, Canada beat Finland 5–3, while Sweden beat Russia 4–3.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After the final period of the final, the match was a 2–2 tie, resulting in a shoot-out.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After six shots, it was tied 2–2 until Sweden's Peter Forsberg beat Corey Hirsch, making the Swedes win after Paul Kariya missed his shot.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This led to Tomas Jonsson, Håkan Loob and Mats Näslund becoming the first three members of the Triple Gold Club.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Italy, Germany and Austria collected all the medals in the luge events.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Germany's Georg Hackl won the men's singles, making him the first to defend an Olympic title in the event in thirty years.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] He finished ahead of Austria's Markus Prock and Italy's Armin Zöggeler.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the doubles, the two Italian teams finished on top, with Kurt Brugger and Wilfried Huber winning ahead of Hansjörg Raffl and Norbert Huber.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the women's singles, Italy's Gerda Weissensteiner won ahead of Germany's Susi Erdmann and Austria's Andrea Tagwerker.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The own debuts was start Nedžad Lomigora from Bosnia and Herzegovina, Marco Feder from Liechtenstein, Sminon J.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Payne from Bermuda, Paul Hix from United Kingdom, Josef Svarek from Slovakia, Roger White from Australia.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Although the events were the same, since the 1992 Games there was a rule change so that instead of jumping three times and taking the points for the best two, the competitors only jumped twice.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the individual normal hill/15 km, Japan's Kenji Ogiwara had only lost a single event in the season's World Cup, but came in sixth on the hill, which was won by Norway's Fred Børre Lundberg.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] He won the event after finishing eight-best in the skiing, ahead of Japan's Takanori Kono, Norway's Bjarte Engen Vik and Ogiwara in fourth.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the team normal hill/3 x 10 km, Japan finished first, third and fifth among the jumpers, giving them a 5:07 minute lead over Norway and finishing 4:49 minutes ahead.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Short track speed skating was dominated by South Korea, who won four of the six events.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After the discipline's debut in 1992, 1994 featured two new events, the men's 500 meters and the women's 1000 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] South Korea's Chae Ji-Hoon won the men's 500 meters, while taking silver on the 1000 meters behind countryman Kim Ki-Hoon, who defended his 1992 gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The bronze was won by Canada's Marc Gagnon, who won the B final.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the A final, countryman Derrick Campbell was obstructed by Great Britain's Nicky Gooch, who was disqualified.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Campbell got up and started celebrating his bronze medal, when he discovered he had not completed the race.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the men's 5000 meter relay, South Korea did not enter after a fall in the sole qualifying event, which took place in March 1993.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Canada fell during the final, which saw Italy take a clear victory ahead of the United States, who were marginally ahead of Australia.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The United States' Eric Flaim became the first to take Olympic medals in both short track and long track speed skating, while Australia took its first Winter Olympic medal ever.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Six people took the individual medals in the women's events, with the United States' Cathy Turner defending her 1992 gold on the 500 meters and South Korea's Chun Lee-Kyung taking the gold in 1000 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] South Korea won the 3000 meter relay with a team of four girls under 19.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] At 13, Kim Yoon-Mi became the world's youngest Olympic gold medalist.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Norway won three of the six individual medals, with Norway's Espen Bredesen winning the normal hill ahead of Norway's Lasse Ottesen and Germany's Dieter Thoma.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the large hill, Germany's Jens Weißflog won ahead of Bredesen and Austria's Andreas Goldberger.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the large hill team, the 1994 Games introduced new rules whereby all four jumps in each round counted, and not just the best three.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Neither Norway nor Finland, who between them had won all but one former Olympic team jump, managed to collect a medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The event became a duel between Germany and Japan, with only a point separating them after the first round of jumps.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Masahiko Harada had the last jump, and would secure a gold if he managed 105 meters but lost his 'cool' mistiming his leap and landed at 97.5 meters, giving the gold to the Germans.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In 1989, the International Skating Union mandated that, from the 1994 Olympics onwards, speed skating events would be held indoors to avoid interference from wind and weather conditions in the competitions.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The 1994 Games also introduced a new system of qualification rules, limiting the number of participants in the men's 5000 meters and women's 3000 meters to 32, and only allowing the 16 best in each of these events to participate in the men's 10000 meters and the women's 5000 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Norway's Johann Olav Koss took three golds, in the men's 1,500 meters, 5000 meters and 10000 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In the latter two, he finished ahead of fellow countryman Kjell Storelid.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The men's 500 meters was won by Russia's Aleksandr Golubev ahead of fellow countryman Sergey Klevchenya, while the men's 1000 meters was won by American Dan Jansen.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] For women, American Bonnie Blair defended her two 1992 golds in 500 meters and 1000 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Austria's Emese Hunyady won the 1500 meters ahead of Russia's Svetlana Bazhanova and Germany's Gunda Niemann.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] However, Bazhanova took gold ahead of Nemeth-Hunyady on the 3000 meters, with Germany's Claudia Pechstein in third.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Pechstein would go on to win the 5000 meters ahead of Niemann.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] At the closing ceremonies, also held at Lysgårdsbakken, all spectators were handed a flashlight with the inscription "Remember Sarajevo"—the host of the 1984 Winter Olympics which was at worst moment of the Bosnian War, the Siege of Sarajevo.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The first entrants on the stage were Liv Ullmann and Thor Heyerdahl, followed by the athletes' precession.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] After the Olympic flag had been transferred to Nagano mayor Tasuka Tsukada, speeches were held by Lillehammer mayor Audun Tron, Heiberg and Samaranch.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The latter used his speech to remind about Sarajevo's situation, before giving Heiberg IOC's gold medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Artistic presentations followed with many of the themes from the opening ceremony.At the 15-minute presentation as the next host city, Nagano was presented to world as a modern Yama-uba, also the 1998 Winter Olympics mascots, the Snowlets, was also presented on a public eye for the first time.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Of the 2,200 people performing in the opening and closing ceremonies, only 50 were professionals.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The games were spread out over ten venues in five municipalities in two counties, Oppland and Hedmark.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer, with 25,000 inhabitants, and Hamar and Gjøvik, both with 27,000 inhabitants, are all situated on the lake Mjøsa.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Gjøvik and Hamar are located 45 and 54 kilometers (28 and 34 mi) south of Lillehammer.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Hunderfossen is located 15 kilometers (9.3 mi) north of Lillehammer, but lies within the municipality. Øyer and Ringebu, both with just under 5,000 inhabitants, are located 18 and 50 kilometers (11 and 31 mi) north of Lillehammer, in the valley Gudbrandsdalen.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer had four venues, Hamar had two venues, while Hunderfossen, Gjøvik, Øyer and Ringebu had one venue each.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In Lillehammer, Lysgårdsbakken features twin ski jumping hills.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The large hill has a hill size of 138 and a critical point of 120, while the normal hill has a hill size of 100 and a critical point of 90.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The hill has capacity for 35,000 spectators and hosted, in addition to the ski jumping events, the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Birkebeineren Skistadion featured cross-country skiing and biathlon, with the stadium itself having a capacity for 31,000 spectators during cross-country skiing and 13,500 during biathlon.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] In addition, spectators could watch from along the tracks.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Kanthugen Freestyle Arena featured a capacity for 15,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] All the outdoor skiing arenas had free areas, which saw up to 25,000 extra spectators at the team jump and 75,000 extra spectators at the 50 km.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Lillehammer Olympic Bobsleigh and Luge Track is located at Hunderfossen.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] It had a capacity for 10,000 spectators and is the only bobsleigh and luge track in the Nordic countries.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Ice hockey was played at two venues, in Håkons Hall in Lillehammer and Gjøvik Olympic Cavern Hall in Gjøvik.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Håkons Hall has a capacity for 10,500 spectators, and also features the Norwegian Olympic Museum.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Cavern Hall is built as a man-made cave and had a capacity for 5,300 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Skating events took place at two venues in Hamar.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Vikingskipet had a capacity for 10,600 spectators and featured speed skating events, while figure skating and short-track speed skating were held at Hamar Olympic Amphitheatre.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Alpine skiing was split between two ski resorts: Hafjell in Øyer and Kvitfjell in Ringebu.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The former was used for the slalom and giant slalom, while the latter hosted downhill and super-G.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Spectators relied heavily on the use of buses and trains for transportation.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Downtown Lillehammer and the axis between Lillehammer and Oslo were the most limiting areas, and the Norwegian State Railways ran up to 22 trains per day between Oslo and Lillehammer.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Trains were also used northwards towards Trondheim, while other areas were served by bus.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] All the venues were located along railway lines, making use of spectators walking from the stations to the venues to limit road congestion, although special services were available for disabled people.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Shuttle buses were established between venues and also connected to park and ride facilities.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] A record 67 nations participated in the 1994 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] These Games were the first to implement stricter qualifying standards that prevented low-performing athletes from competing without meeting minimum requirements.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] As a consequence, eleven "warm-weather countries" that signed up to take part in the Games were mostly absent because very few of their athletes succeeded in qualifying; the number of African athletes fell from nineteen in 1992 to three in 1994.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] These rules were, however, not applied to bobsled events, enabling the U.S.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Virgin Islands, Trinidad and Tobago and Jamaica to compete in that sport.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] On 25 October 1993, the United Nations General Assembly urged its members to observe the Olympic truce, lasting from seven days before the start of the Games until seven days after the close, making the Lillehammer Olympics the first to observe the truce.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The IOC appealed for a truce in the ongoing Bosnian War and the Siege of Sarajevo, the city that had hosted the 1984 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The former Soviet republics of Armenia, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Ukraine and Uzbekistan participated as independent nations.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This was the first time since the 1912 Summer Olympics that Russia competed independently at the Olympic Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Athletes of these countries previously competed in the Winter Olympics as part of the Soviet Union team until 1991.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The Czech Republic and Slovakia participated for the first time, after the break-up of Czechoslovakia in 1993.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Bosnia and Herzegovina made their Olympic debut, following their independence from Yugoslavia in 1992; the composition of their four-man bob team was one Croat, two Bosniaks and a Serb, mirroring the ethnic diversity of the country.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] This was also Israel's first appearance at the Winter Olympics and a member of the European Olympic Committees.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] American Samoa participated for the first time, as did Trinidad and Tobago.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] Russia won the most golds, while Norway won the most medals overall.
[src:bleacher-report/1994-winter-olympics] The following table presents the top ten nations, sorted by gold medals, with the host nation highlighted.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The city of Nagano had previously been a candidate to host the 1940 Winter Olympics (which were later cancelled), as well as the 1972 Winter Olympics, but had been eliminated at the national level by Sapporo on both occasions.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The games hosted 2,176 athletes from 72 nations competing in 7 sports and 68 events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The number of athletes and participating nations were a record at the time.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Games saw the introduction of women's ice hockey, curling and snowboarding.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] National Hockey League players were allowed to participate in the men's ice hockey for the first time.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Azerbaijan, Kenya, Macedonia, Uruguay, and Venezuela made their debut at the Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The athlete who won the most medals at these games was the Russian cross-country skier Larisa Lazutina who won five medals, including three gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Norwegian cross-country skier Bjørn Dæhlie won four medals, including three gold, which took his total Olympic medal total to 12, including eight gold, which is a record for Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Czech men's ice hockey team won the gold medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In Ski Jumping, Kazuyoshi Funaki won two gold medals and one silver for host Japan.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The American Figure skater Tara Lipinski became the youngest champion in Olympic history at the age of 15 years and 255 days.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Germany dominated the medal table with 29 medals, including 12 gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Germany was followed by Norway and Russia, who won 25 and 18 medals respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Canada, which finished fourth in the medal table with 15 medals, including six gold, had its most successful Winter Olympics up until that point.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The host was selected on 15 June 1991, over Salt Lake City, Östersund, Jaca and Aosta.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] They were the third Olympic Games and second Winter Olympics to be held in Japan, after the 1964 Summer Olympics in Tokyo and the 1972 Winter Olympics in Sapporo.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The games were succeeded by the 1998 Winter Paralympics from 5 to 14 March.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] These were the final Winter Olympic Games under the IOC Presidency of Juan Antonio Samaranch.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The hosting of the games improved transportation networks with the construction of the high-speed *Shinkansen*, the Nagano Shinkansen (now the Hokuriku Shinkansen), between Tokyo and Nagano Station, via Ōmiya and Takasaki.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, new highways were built, including the Nagano Expressway and the Jōshin-etsu Expressway and upgrades were made to existing roads.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In 1932, Japan won the rights to host the 1940 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] At that time, organizers of the Summer Olympics had priority in choosing the venue for the Winter Olympics the same year.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Several Japanese cities, including Nagano, prepared a bid.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Sapporo was chosen; however, the games never took place because of World War II.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In 1961, Nagano declared its intention to host the 1968 Winter Olympics but lost to Sapporo, the winning Japanese bid, who lost to Grenoble, France, and Sapporo eventually won the right to host the 1972 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Japanese private sector organizations, in 1983, began publicly discussing a possible bid.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two years later, in 1985, the Nagano Prefectural Assembly, decided to begin the process to bid, for its third time, for a Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The bid committee was established in July 1986, they submitted their bid to the Japanese Olympic Committee (JOC) in November of the same year.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Other Japanese cities that were bidding were Asahikawa, Yamagata, and Morioka.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] 1 June 1988, the JOC selected Nagano in the first round of national voting, receiving 34 of 45 votes.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In 1989, the bid committee was reorganized, with the Japanese Prime Minister as head of the committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The number of committee members was 511.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] On 12 February 1990, the bid delegation presented its candidature at the International Olympic Committee in Lausanne before Juan Antonio Samaranch.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Other candidate cities for the 1998 Olympics were Aosta, Italy; Jaca, Spain; Östersund, Sweden; Salt Lake City, United States, and Sochi, Russian SFSR, Soviet Union (now Russia).
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The host city selection was held in Birmingham, United Kingdom, on 15 June 1991, at the 97th IOC session.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] After the first round of voting, Nagano led, with Aosta and Salt Lake City tied for last.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Aosta was eliminated in a run-off against Salt Lake City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] After the second round of voting, Nagano led with Salt Lake City in second, and Jaca was eliminated.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Following round 3, Nagano continued to lead, with Salt Lake City in second, and Östersund was eliminated.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, Nagano prevailed over Salt Lake City by just 4 votes in the fifth round of voting, becoming the third Japanese city to host the games after Tokyo in 1964 Summer Olympics and Sapporo in 1972.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Nagano, at 36°N, is the southernmost city in the Northern Hemisphere to host the Winter Olympics (1960 Winter Olympics host Squaw Valley, California is 39°N).
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In June 1995, Salt Lake was chosen as the host of the following 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Following a 2002 Winter Olympic bid scandal that occurred in the summer of 2000, Atlanta, host of the 1996 Summer Olympics, Nagano, and Sydney, host of the 2000 Summer Olympics, were suspected of similar improprieties in bidding practices.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Although nothing illegal was ever done, gifts to IOC members were considered morally dubious.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Nagano Olympic bid committee spent approximately $14 million to entertain the 62 International Olympic Committee members and many of their companions.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The precise figures are unknown since Nagano, after the IOC asked that the entertainment expenditures not be made public, destroyed the financial records, according to bid member Junichi Yamaguchi.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Five months after the city was selected, the Nagano Olympic Organizing Committee (NAOC) was created.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Eishiro Saito, Chairman of Japan Business Federation (Keidanren) was selected as president of the committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] There were four Vice Presidents: Goro Yoshimura, the Governor of Nagano Prefecture; Hironoshin Furuhashi, president of the Japanese Olympic Committee; Yoshiaki Tsutsumi, the president of the Ski Association of Japan; and Tasuku Tsukada, the Mayor of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, the Vice Minister of the Ministry of Home Affairs, Tadashi Tsuda, served as director-general.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Tsuda was replaced by Makoto Kobayashi in 1993.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee recognized three goals for the games, which they referred to as "Games from the Heart": promote youth participation, coexistence with nature, create a festival with peace and friendship at its centre.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] To realize the first goal, a camp bringing together 217 young people from 51 countries was created, along with the program of "One school, one country" in Nagano Prefecture.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This program organized cultural exchanges with other countries.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, more than 100,000 tickets were reserved for children.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] For the second point, the organizers attempted to minimize the impact on their nature and the local ecosystem.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Regarding the third point, an international truce organized by the United Nations in 1997 was adopted during the games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In June 1998, four months after the Games, the NAOC presented a donation of US$1 million to the Olympic Museum in Lausanne.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This value come of the revenue of tickets sales and another actions from the committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In October of the same year, NAOC also donated the 3-D high vision theater and some structures that were used in Nagano Olympic Villages to the Olympic Museum.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In February 1999, one year after the Games, the IOC awarded the Nagano the Olympic Cup, and presented the city a replica of the sculpture of stylized athletes raising the Olympic Flag by the Swiss artist Nag Arnoldi.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The costs of construction and of the land of the Olympic venues totaled ¥106.6 billion, approximately 914 million US dollars.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Of this, the Japanese national government spent ¥51.1 billion, the Nagano prefectural government spent ¥29.6 billion, and the cities and towns of Nagano, ¥23.4 billion; Hakuba, ¥1 billion; and Nozawa Onsen, ¥1.1 billion; shared the remaining ¥25.5 billion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The most expensive venue was impressive M-Wave, the indoor rink which hosted the long-track speed skating events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The two ice hockey venues, Big Hat and Aqua Wing Arena cost ¥19.1 and ¥9.1 billion respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The White Ring (arena), which hosted figure skating and short-track speed skating cost ¥14.2 billion, the Spiral, which hosted bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton, cost ¥10.1 billion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Another ¥8.6 billion was spent on the Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium, ¥7 billion for Snow Harp – the cross-country skiing venue, and ¥3 billion for the biathlon venue at Nozawa Onsen Snow Resort.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee financed all costs, totaling ¥113.9 billion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] It spent ¥99.4 billion for operational expenses, ¥21.6 billion for public relations, ¥20.7 billion for installations, ¥18.4 billion for telecommunications, ¥15.9 billion for running the competitions, and ¥14.4 billion for administration.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Television rights were worth ¥35.4 billion, and marketing earned ¥31.3 billion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The total cost of the Nagano Games is estimated to have been US$15.25 billion (in 2015), of which the largest factor in the cost of the games was the extension of the shinkansen to Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Nagano is situated at the Japanese Alps area and receives large snowfalls every year.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] These combined to make transportation an important challenge for the organizing committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, the Olympic Village was a distance of 7 kilometers from the center of the city, and sporting events were spread over five surrounding cities.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The complicating matters were that many of the venues had one single road in-out, which limited possibilities and led to traffic jams.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] To improve access to Nagano, the government decided to link the prefecture with the high-speed *shinkansen* train network.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Called Nagano Shinkansen (now the Hokuriku Shinkansen), it was inaugurated five months before the start of the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This reduced by half the travel time between Tokyo and Nagano, to 79 minutes for 221 kilometers.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The length of the track between Takasaki Station and Nagano Station is 125.7 km, which includes 63.4 km of tunnels.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The high speed train network carried 655,000 passengers during the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two highways, the Nagano Expressway and the Jōshin-etsu Expressway, were also built in the Nagano region.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In May 1993, the 75.8-kilometer section of the Nagano Expressway was completed, and in October 1997, the 111.4 kilometer section of the Jōshin-etsu Expressway was completed.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, another 114.9 kilometers of roads within Nagano Prefecture were improved.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Transportation systems for the Games ran for 33 days, from the opening of the Athletes Village until 3 days after the Paralympics closing ceremony, when the Village was decommissioned from its functions.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 64% of the athletes arrived between 1 and 6 February, and 74% left Nagano between 22 and 25 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Logistical operations were directed from the operational centre situated at the Organizing Committee headquarters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two regional logistical minor hubs were created in Hakuba and Yamanouchi, as well as a traffic center for buses and cars in Karuizawa.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Originally it was expected that both athletes and media delegations would arrive entirely via Narita International Airport, which did not happen given the high demand for plane tickets.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] So some delegations had to arrive via Kansai International Airport and Chubu Centrair International Airport in Nagoya The members of the IOC and the delegations who arrived in Narita traveled to Nagano via Shinkansen.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] To improve transportation for spectators, the number and hours of local trains were extended.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] During the heaviest traffic days, more cars and buses were put in service and up to 68 parking areas, for 8,000 vehicles were at available for various Olympic delegations, and another 17 parking areas for 23,000 cars for spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 1,200 vehicles had navigation systems which transmitted their locations in a GPS system.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] As one of the principal aims of the Games was to respect nature, many vehicles were considered ecological or semi-ecological.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, there were more than 100 electric vehicles, hybrid mini-buses and other environmentally-friendly vehicles.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The emblem of the 1998 Winter Olympics consisted of a stylized snow flower with each petal representing an athlete participating in a winter sport.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The figure could also represent a snowflake, or a mountain flower, which refers to the importance of the natural environment to the city of Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Similarly, Tokyo used cherry blossoms in its logo for its candidature for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Landor Associates conceived the official mascots that were used by the communication team for the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] They consisted of four owlets, Sukki, Nokki, Lekki and Tsukki, also called *Snowlets*.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The names were chosen from more than 47,000 suggestions.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Four represents the number of years between each Olympic Games, and also represent the four elements, fire, air, earth, and water.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The official poster for the Games was designed by the graphic designer Masuteru Aoba presented a thrush perched on ski poles with light in the background shining on snow-capped mountain peaks.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Here, as with the emblem and the mascots, the importance of the natural environment in these Olympic Games and a desire to create harmony between athletes and the natural surroundings are shown.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition to the official poster, a separate poster was created for the opening ceremony.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Marketing for the games cost the organizing committee 5.9 billion yen.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] These Olympic Games were sponsored by 11 worldwide partners, 8 gold partners, and 18 official supports and suppliers.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Marketing revenues for sponsoring or for the rights to use the emblems and mascots of the Games totaled 31.3 billion yen.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Sukki, Nokki, Lekki and Tsukki, also known as the Snowlets, are the 1998 Winter Olympic mascots and are four snowy owls.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] They represent respectively fire (Sukki), air (Nokki), earth (Lekki) and water (Tsukki) and together they represent the four major islands of Japan.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Sponsors were permitted to use the emblem and mascots as long as consent was obtained from the International Olympic Committee, Japanese Olympic Committee, and the NAOC.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Hospitality packages for sponsors included priority for accommodations, tickets, and transportation services.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Sponsor Hospitality Village, next to the Nagano Olympic Stadium, welcomed 32,000 guests.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] To promote awareness of the sponsors, advertising was done in various media from 1995, and on banners and buses immediately before the games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Dick Pound noted, during the Games, the excellence of the marketing program, citing the "*perfect example of how the private and public sectors can work together*".
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Games had 11 Worldwide Olympic Partners, eight Gold Sponsors and 18 Official Supporters and Suppliers.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] From 7 February 1997, the organizing committee put up for sale 1,286,000 tickets for the various competitions and ceremonies.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The number of tickets sold was 1,149,615, which represented 89.4% of available tickets.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Including people connected to the Games, the total number of spectators was 1,275,529.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This number was slightly higher than in 1994 as a result of the greater availability of tickets.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This reflected the total capacity of the arenas used, which were mostly larger than those used four years earlier but slightly lower than the 1988 Winter Olympics in Calgary.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Tickets sales were a success in the domestic market, as the Japanese people finished the process of purchase with a reservation list of 6 million.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] For the most popular events, a lottery system was used.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In total, ticket sales raised 10.5 billion yen for the organizing committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The ice hockey matches represented 295,802 tickets sold, 26% of the total.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Tickets sold for alpine skiing totaled 166,092; for ski jumping, 96,000, and speed skating, 93,000.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] For multiple sports, ski jumping, Nordic combined, freestyle skiing, all three skating disciplines, bobsleigh, and curling, as well as the ceremonies, all tickets were sold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] By contrast, due to the local demands and low interest only 56.6% of the 146,000 available tickets for cross-country skiing were sold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] During the 1998 Winter Olympics, a total of fourteen sports venues, all within Nagano Prefecture, were used.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Construction of these venues lasted 7 years between 1990 and 1997, with construction and land costs totaling ¥106.6 billion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The most expensive venue constructed for the games was the M-Wave who hosted the speed skating events.This venue is in a distance from 5 kilometers from Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Between March 1996 and November 1997, these sites were tested with 16 different World Championship events, World Cups, and another international competitions to allow the organizers to prepare for the running of the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Five new venues were used, localized all inside city of Nagano urban area.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The project to build the Olympic Stadium and the 4 indoor arenas was planned even before the plans for the Olympic bid.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] However, these plans were accelerated soon after the submission of the proposal to the Japanese Olympic Committee, as the city had no infrastructure available for any type of event available.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Nagano Olympic Stadium is the main sporting venue of the south of city, is on nearby Shinonoi Station, and approximately 9 kilometers from Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Outside from their structure, the stadium, who resembles a cherry blossom, one of main symbols of Japan.During the Games, the arena was exclusively used for the opening and closing ceremonies and, when added to the temporary infrastructure, its capacity reached 50.000.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Big Hat Arena was the ice hockey main venue.is approximately located 2 km from Nagano Station and have a capacity of 10,104 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Another arena, the Aqua Wing Arena, the second ice hockey venue.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Shaped like a wing, it had a capacity of 6000 during the Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] After the Games, it was modified into a public indoor swimming with a 25m pool.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Aqua Wing is approximately 5 kilometers from Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Its closest stations are Kita-Nagano Station and Asahi Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] M-Wave, the speed skating venue, is the first indoor track speed skating venue in Japan.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] It was built to accommodate 10,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The venue, which gets its name from its M-shape, representing the surrounding mountains and harmonize with the skyline, is approximately 5 kilometers from Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, White Ring, with a maximum capacity of 7.351 spectators, was built for figure skating and short track speed skating.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] White Ring, which is used as a public gymnasium, is approximately 6 kilometers from Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Hakuba village is situated 50 kilometers west of the city of Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Hakuba hosted three Olympics venues Alpine skiing's downhill, super-G and combined were situated at Happo'one Resort.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Three courses between altitudes of 840 meters and 1,765 meters were used, one for the men's, women's and combined for both men's and women's.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The site had a capacity of 20,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium was the first ski jump built in Japan with parallel 90 and 120 K-point hills.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The ski jumping stadium could accommodate 45,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Snow Harp Kamishiro was built for cross country skiing and Nordic combined.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] It includes three tracks of 4.8, 4.8, and 7.8 kilometers.The stadium area is near 1.2 km2.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In total, Snow Harp has 19 kilometers of tracks.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Up to 20,000 spectators could be accommodated.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Nozawa Onsen Ski Resort, in the town of Nozawaonsen, was site of biathlon.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Nozawa is approximately 50 kilometers north of Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] At Nozawa Onsen, the stadium was built around six existing tracks.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two tracks, of 4 kilometers and 7 kilometers, were used for the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The stadium could accommodate 20,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two sites in the town of Yamanouchi, approximately 30 kilometers northeast of Nagano, were used.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Giant slalom was held at Mount Yakebitai at Shiga Kogen Resort, at an altitude between 1,530 and 1,969 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The site could accommodate 20,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Also in Shiga Kogen, at Mount Higashidate, giant slalom events in Alpine skiing and snowboarding were held.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Kanbayashi Snowboard Park was the site of the half pipe event in snowboarding .
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The track is 120 meters long and 15 meters wide, with walls of 3.5 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] 10,000 spectators could be accommodated at Kanbayashi.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The town of Iizuna, approximately 12 kilometers northwest of Nagano, was the site of freestyle skiing and bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton at Iizuna Kogen Ski Area.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] 8,000 spectators could watch the free style skiing on a course that 250 meters long and 12,000 could the jumps.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Spiral, which held the sledding events, was the first artificially refrigerated track in Asia.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] It is 1700 meters long, with a difference in height of 114 meters and 15 turns.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] At the Spiral, approximately 40,000 saplings, mainly beech and oak, were planted two per square meter, as part of the environmental stewardship committed during the Winter Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The site could accommodate 10,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, the town of Karuizawa, approximately 80 kilometers southeast of Nagano, hosted the curling events at Kazakoshi Park Arena.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The venue was built as a multi-purpose venue.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Its maximum capacity is 1,924 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The same venue also hosted the equestrian events at the 1964 Summer Olympics, thus becoming the first venue to host both the Summer Olympics and Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] To accommodate the athletes and officials during the Games, the main Olympic Village was constructed in Imai district, this complex approximately 7 kilometers south of Nagano Station.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Along with the construction of the village, Imai Station was opened in 1997.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The responsibility for the construction of these buildings lay with the Nagano City, as a future public and low coast residential housing and was loaned to the organizing committee during the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The main Village occupies an area that is 19 hectares, composed of 23 buildings with a total of 1,032 apartments.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Temporary infrastrure were also available during the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Village was open for the Olympics from 24 January to 25 February 1998 and 1 to 19 March for the Paralympics, and accommodated nearby 4,000 people during the two events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Several prominent people were recognized as faces of the Olympic Village, including the *Honorary Mayor* Yasuko Konoe, *Mayor* Shozo Sasahara, and *Deputy Mayors* Takanori Kono, Hiroko Chiba, and Shunichi Bobby Hirai.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] As the curling venue was in Karuizawa, 90 kilometers away, a satellite village was built in Karuizawa, 7 kilometers from the arena.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, a section of the Shiga Kogen Resort, 58 kilometers from the Olympic Village, was reserved for 180 snowboarders and officials.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition to athletes and officials, members of the Olympic and Paralympic family and other personnel were housed in 900 hotels and another structures in Nagano and surrounding regions, which represented 234,207 nights between 24 January to 25 February 1998.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic and Paralympic families stayed in the Kokusai 21 Hotel in downtown Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In total, the Olympic and Paralympic families included 18,350 people.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, two media villages were built in the districts of Yanagimachi, near Nagano Station, and Asahi, across the street from the M-Wave.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic torch was lit by sunlight during the ceremony held Temple of Hera at Olympia, Greece on 19 December 1997.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Vassilis Dimitriadis, a Greek alpine skier started the Greek leg towards Athens where the handover ceremony was held at the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The flame burned from 27 to 30 December in the Ginza yard, and from 31 December to 4 January in the Yoyogi Park.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] On the morning on that day the flame was split into three and taken by plane to three destinations: the Kantō route, starting from Hokkaido; the Pacific Ocean route, starting from Kagoshima; and the Sea of Japan route starting in Okinawa.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] On 23 January evening, the three flames arrived on Nagano Prefecture after 120 stops.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, these three routes were unified in the city of Nagano in on the night of 6 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The following day, after traveling through each district of the city, the relays simultaneously arrived at the central square where three former athletes passed the flames to three members of the organizing committee who lit a celebration cauldron gathering the flame into one.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] After that, the unified flame was used to light another torch held by Juan Antonio Samaranch.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In the early hours of the 7 February morning, the final leg started and the flame travelled another 10 kilometers to the Olympic Stadium and the figure skater Midori Ito lit the cauldron at Nagano Olympic Stadium during the opening ceremonies.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Flame Relay in Japan was sponsored by Coca-Cola, lasted 33 days and travelled 1,162 kilometers.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] A group of 5.5 million people took part in relay activities.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Over the distance of the relay, the flame was always followed by a group of six people: the torchbearer who carried the flame, some who accompanied the carrier, and four people in supporting roles, for a total of 6,901 people.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, each leg was followed by two groups of 11 vehicles and more than 20 people.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The torch was shaped like a traditional Japanese *taimatsu* torch.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] It was made of aluminum, was 55 centimeters long, and weighed 1.3 kilograms when it was assembled.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The exterior of the torch was coloured silver, to represent winter.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Runners wore blue and white uniforms mixing blue as the main colour of the look of the games and the white as snow.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The runners' uniforms included logos for the Nagano Olympics and the Olympic Games, a logo of the relay, and of Coca-Cola.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] 72 nations participated in the 1998 Winter Olympic Games for a total of 2,176 athletes, of which 787 were female and 1,389 were male.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] With the addition of five countries and another 439 athletes since the 1994 Winter Olympic Games at Lillehammer, Norway, these were the largest Winter Olympics ever at the time.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The nations of Azerbaijan, Kenya, Macedonia, Uruguay, and Venezuela participated in their first Winter Olympic Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Iran returned to the Winter games after a 22-year absence, and North Korea, India and Ireland returned after 6 years.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Yugoslavia appeared again as the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Five countries, Fiji, Mexico, San Marino, American Samoa, and Senegal, which were at the 1994 Games, did not participate in 1998.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The United States had the largest athlete delegation with 186, followed by host Japan with 156, Canada with 144, and Germany with 125.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Despite the large number of participating delegations, 40 of the 72 delegations had less than 10 athletes, with 12 nations having one sole athlete.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] 15 nations had between 11 and 50 athletes, 11 nations had between 51 and 100 athletes, and six nations had more than 101 athletes.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Nations that participated in the ice hockey tournaments generally had the largest athlete delegations.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] With the exception of Norway and Switzerland, all 12 national delegations with 60 or more athletes participated in either or both of the female or male ice hockey tournaments.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The number in parentheses represents the number of athletes participating in official events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The 1998 Winter Olympics were held in a period of 15 days, from 7–22 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The number of events increased from 61 at the 1994 Winter Olympics to 68 in 1998.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Two sports, curling and snowboarding were added to the program, as was women's ice hockey.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This increased the number of sports to seven, and the number of disciplines to 14.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The sporting program started and ended with men's ice hockey.The first matches started at 4:00 pm on 7 February featuring Kazakhstan defeating Italy 5–3, and Slovakia tying Austria 2–2.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony took place at the Nagano Olympic Stadium, Nagano, Japan, on the late morning of 7 February 1998.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Japanese figure skater, Midori Ito, the first female skater to land seven triple jumps in a free skating competition and also the first Asian world champion in 1989, and the silver medalist at the 1992 Winter Olympics, lit the cauldron during the ceremony.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Seiji Ozawa, a Japanese conductor, directed an orchestra from five continents (Beijing, Berlin, Cape Town, New York City, and Sydney - and the crowd in the Nagano Olympic Stadium), to perform the fourth movement of Beethoven's Symphony No.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This was the first time a simultaneous international audio-visual performance had been achieved and was also the last time that the Olympics Opening ceremonies were held on a morning timeslot in the host city.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In all, 2,302 athletes from 72 National Olympic Committees participated in the Games, including 814 female athletes and 1488 male athletes.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Both the number of participating delegations and the number of athletes participating in the competition were, at the time, the most ever hosted at the Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The version used at the time of the Olympic Charter, approved on September 5, 1997.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Charter in force at that time determined that (skating, ice hockey, and curling) were had to be at the event venues immediately after the finalsThe version used at the time of the Olympic Charter, approved on September 5, 1997.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] For the medal ceremonies, a total 167,200 tickets were sold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] National and international artists presented every evening at the place before the medal presentations.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The gold, silver, and bronze medals each measured 80 mm in diameter and 9.7 mm in thickness.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The gold medals weighed 256 g, the silver 250 g, and the bronze 230 g.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The medals were made using a traditional Japanese lacquerware technique known as 漆器 (*shikki*), in which a brass core is imprinted with the design by layering gold powder onto the wet lacquer using a method called maki-e.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] On the front of the medals are borders of olive leaves, and in the center, a *maki-e* morning sun rises over a cloisonné emblem of the Nagano Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] On the reverse side, the snowflower emblem of the Games sits above a *maki-e* image of the mountains surrounding Nagano glowing in the morning sunrise.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The initial lacquering was handcrafted by artisans from the town Kiso, Nagano, and the metals components were added at the Mint Bureau of the Japanese Ministry of Finance.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition to the medals awarded to the athletes in each event, more than 19,000 commemorative medals were given to all athletes, officials, International Olympic Committee members, media personnel, volunteers and others.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] These medals, made by the Mint Bureau in cooperation with NAOC, were made from an alloy of 90% copper and 10% zinc.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] As the Olympic Charter also determines, diplomas, written in Japanese, French, and English, were given to the top eight finishers in each event, and every participant also received a commemorative diploma.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The closing ceremonies, like those of the opening, took place in the Nagano Olympic Stadium, with 50,000 tickets sold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Akihito, the Emperor of Japan at the time, and his wife Empress Michiko were also present.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] After the athletes entered, hundreds of drums were beat and a traditional hose and lion dance was presented.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] During the Antwerp Ceremony, Tasuku Tsukada, then mayor of Nagano presented the Olympic Flag to Deedee Corradini, then mayor of Salt Lake City, the host of the 2002 Winter Olympics.After the handover of the flag, the then IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch declared the games closed.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] This was followed by a performance from the Japanese singer Anri when the Olympic Cauldron was extinguished.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The ceremony ended with the words "*Sayonara, Arigato*" ("Goodbye, Thank you"), a major fireworks performance accompanied by a party with the song: "Ile Aiye" performed by Japanese pop group Agharta.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In all, 24 of the 72 participating National Olympic Committees at these Games won at least one medal, as shown in the table below.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] A total of 15 countries won at least one gold medal and 18 nations won two or more medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Germany finished on top of the table with 29 medals, including 12 gold, nine silver, and eight bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Germany, which finished in third place in the medal standings at the 1994 Winter Olympics, won most of its medals in Alpine skiing, speed skating, and luge, in which it won all three gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] German female athletes won 22 of the country's 29 medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Norway finished again in second, with 25 medals, including nine won in cross-country skiing and five in biathlon.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Host The host country, Japan had a historic campaign.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] The country, which until then had only won 3 gold medals in the history of the Winter Games, finished the Games with 5.The japanese team also won 1 silver and 4 bronze medals, in a total of 10.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Australia became the second country from the Southern Hemisphere to win a medal, a bronze in alpine skiing.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Also, Denmark each won your first ever medal, the silver at women's curling.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, Bulgaria and the Czech Republic each won their first gold medals at a Winter Olympics in women's biathlon and men's ice hockey respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p01] Finally, Kazakhstan won its first medal from a female athlete.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 1998 Winter Olympics featured a record 68 medal events over 14 disciplines in seven sports.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In relation to the 1994 Winter Olympics, seven new events were added to the Winter Olympic program.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Officially absent since the 1924 Winter Olympics, curling returned to the Olympic program (the sport was demonstrated in 1932,1988 and 1992) with 2 events (one tournament for men and one for women).
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] For the first time, an ice hockey tournament for women was included.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Another change was the addition of another discipline in alpine skiing: snowboarding with 4 events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The biathlon competitions took place at Nozawa Onsen Snow Resort, north of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The six events were the sprint, individual, and relay, for both men and women.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 183 athletes took part, including 96 men and 87 women from 32 countries.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Norway and Germany each won five medals, with Uschi Disl from the latter country winning one gold, one silver, and one bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first event was the women's 15 km individual race that took place in falling snow on 9 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The surprise gold medalist was Ekaterina Dafovska from Bulgaria, who had been ranked 51st at the previous Biathlon World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Her gold medal was the first-ever Bulgarian gold medal at a Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Her time was 54:52.0, with only one target missed.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Olena Petrova from Ukraine won the silver, 17.8 seconds behind, and Uschi Disl won the bronze, 25.9 seconds behind Dafovska.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first men's event, the 20 km individual race, took place on 11 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Norwegian Halvard Hanevold missed his second-last target, but finished first in a time of 56:16.4.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Italian Pieralberto Carrara, who missed no targets, target, won the silver, 5.05 seconds behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Belarusian Alexei Aidarov was 30.1 seconds behind the Norwegian, and won the bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The bobsleigh competitions took place at the Spiral, in Iizuna, just north of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Spiral course measured 1700 m in length, with fifteen curves, descended 113 m from start to finish, and included two short uphill sections.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The two events were the two-man and four-man, for men only.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Female competitors would begin competing in the two woman events at the subsequent Winter Olympics, the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 156 athletes took part from 28 countries.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The bobsleigh events resulted in two ties, for the two-man gold and for the four-man bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] This was the first time in Olympic bobsleigh history that there were ties for the medal positions.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Christoph Langen and Markus Zimmermann won bronze in the two-man competition and were part of the winning four-man team.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, Germany win one gold and one bronze; Italy and Canada also won one gold each when the two-man team.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first time since the 1968 Winter Olympics did more than four countries win bobsleigh medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In addition, Germany and Switzerland were the only two countries to place two sleds in the top ten of either event.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 1996 and 1997 Bobsleigh World Champions were teams from Germany and Italy respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] However, Günther Huber and Antonio Tartaglia from Italy tied with the two-man team from Canada, Pierre Lueders and Dave MacEachern for the gold medal, each with combined times of 3:37.24.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German team of Christoph Langen and Markus Zimmermann were 0.65 seconds behind, and were awarded the bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the four-man event, bad weather restricted the competition to three runs only.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German team of Christoph Langen, Markus Zimmermann, Marco Jakobs and Olaf Hampel completed the three runs in 2:39.41 for the gold medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Swiss team of Marcel Rohner, Markus Nüssli, Markus Wasser, and Beat Seitz finished second with a time of 2:40.01.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Two teams, were awarded bronze medals after completing the three runs in 2:40.06.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] These were the team from Great Britain, made up of Sean Olsson, Dean Ward, Courtney Rumbolt, and Paul Attwood; and the team from France, composed of Bruno Mingeon, Emmanuel Hostache, Éric Le Chanony, and Max Robert.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Curling was included in the program for the Nagano Olympics in 1993 following discussions that had begun in 1992.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At the time, it was considered that curling was making its official Olympic debut following its appearance as a demonstration sport at the 1932, 1988, and 1992.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At the Games in Nagano, both the men's and the women's curling tournament took place at Kazakoshi Park Arena in Karuizawa, Nagano, 30 minutes by bullet train (*shinkansen*) south of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Eight teams played a total of seven games in the round robin in both tournaments, with the four best teams going to the semifinals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Canada won gold in the women's competition and silver in the men's; Switzerland won the gold in the men's tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the men's tournament, the Mike Harris team from Canada easily completed the round-robin tournament winning six of its seven games, only losing to the Eigil Ramsfjell team from Norway.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the semi-finals, the Canadian team defeated Tim Somerville's team from the United States by a score of 7–1; and in the other semi-final, the team from Switzerland led by Patrick Hürlimann defeated Norway 8–7.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the gold medal game, Switzerland shocked Canada by winning 9–3.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the bronze medal game, Eigil Ramsfjell's team from Norway defeated Tim Somerville's USA team by a score of 9–4.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the women's tournament, the Sandra Schmirler team from Canada and the Elisabet Gustafson team from Sweden easily completed the round-robin tournament, with both teams winning six of their seven games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Canada only lost to the Dordi Nordby team from Norway, and Sweden's only loss was to Canada.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the semi-finals, the Canadian team defeated the team led by Kirsty Hay representing team Great Britain by a score of 6–5; and in the other semi-final, the team from Denmark led by Helena Blach Lavrsen defeated Sweden 7–5.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the gold medal game, Canada defeated Denmark by a score of 7–5.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the bronze medal game, Elisabet Gustafso's team from Sweden defeated Kirsty Hay's GB team by a score of 10–6.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The ice hockey matches took place at two purpose-built arenas in Nagano City, Big Hat and Aqua Wing Arena.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The ice hockey events were significant for two reasons: the first Olympic ice hockey tournament for women and the participation of players from the NHL, which scheduled its first ever mid-season break.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Czech Republic defeated Russia in the gold medal game for the men's title, and the United States defeated Canada in the gold medal game for the women's title.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The men's competition began on 7 February with eight teams playing in two groups of four, Group A and B, with each team playing three games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The winners of these two groups, Kazakhstan and Belarus, advanced to join Groups C and D, composed of the six highest ranked men's national ice hockey teams in the world.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Russia, Czech Republic, and Finland were joined by Kazakhstan in Group C; Canada, Sweden, and the United States were joined by Belarus in Group D.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] On 22 February, with 10,010 spectators in attendance at Big Hat, the Czech Republic defeated Russia in the gold medal game, 1–0, with the lone goal of the match scored with 12 minutes remaining.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Finland defeated Canada for the bronze medal by a score of 3–2.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first women's ice hockey world championship, a biennial tournament, took place in 1990.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Discussions to include women's ice hockey at the 1998 games began in 1992, and it was decided to include them in the program in 1993.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The tournament included six teams playing in a one-group round-robin tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The top two team advanced to the gold medal game, and the teams ranked third and fourth played in the bronze medal match.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The favorites were the Canadians, who had won the three previous world championships, with the Americans finishing second each time.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the round-robin tournament, the Americans finished first, with the Canadians second.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the last round-robin game, the United States handily defeated Canada, 7–4, with the two teams scoring nine goals in the third period.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the gold medal match, with 8,626 fans in attendance at Big Hat, the U.S. again defeated Canada, 3–1.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Team Finland defeated Team China 4–1 for the bronze medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The luge competitions took place in Iizuna, Nagano, at the Spiral (Nagano Bobsleigh-Luge Park), the first purpose-built permanent bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton track in Asia.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 24 nations took part in the luge events, with four countries, India, South Korea, New Zealand, and Venezuela making their Olympic debut in luge events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] There were three events, men's single, women's single, and doubles.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Germany won all three gold medals, one silver, and one bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The United States won one silver and one bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Italy and Austria rounded out the medal table.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first event with 24 lugers was the men's singles.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Each athlete completed four runs over two days, 8 and 9 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German athlete, Georg Hackl, who had won gold at the 1992 Winter Olympics and 1994 Winter Olympics, had entered the competition winless in the 1997–1998 season.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Hackl raced in a newly designed luge and aerodynamic shoes.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Several team protested but these protests were rejected.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Hackl dominated all four races, and finished with a time of 3:18.436, half a second ahead of the Italian Armin Zöggeler.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Zöggeler finished .154 seconds ahead of Jens Müller of Germany, who had won gold at the 1988 Winter Olympics when he competed for East Germany.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] On 10 and 11 February, the women's singles event took place, with each athlete completing four runs.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The race for gold was very tight between two German athletes, Silke Kraushaar and Barbara Niedernhuber, with Kraushaar winning by .002 seconds, with a total time of 3:23.779 – the smallest margin of victory ever at the Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Angelika Neuner of Austria won the bronze, 0.474 seconds behind the gold medalist.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The two-race doubles competition, which in theory were open to females, consisted of 17 male pairs.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Germans Stefan Krauße and Jan Behrendt, who had competed together for 14 years, won the gold medal with a time of 1:41.105.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Two American teams won silver and bronze, with Chris Thorpe and Gordy Sheer finishing .022 seconds behind the gold medalists and Brian Martin and Mark Grimmette a further .09 seconds behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The win by Krauße and Behrendt was their four medal at the Olympics since they won silver at the 1988 Winter Olympics when they competed for East Germany.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] This was the first time since the introduction of luge at the 1964 Winter Olympics that athletes other than those from Austria, Germany, Italy, and the Soviet Union won medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The figure skating events took place at the White Ring (arena), an indoor arena built for the Games in Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Medals were awarded in four events: men's and women's singles, pair skating, and ice dance.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The pairs event took place from 8–10 February, followed by the men's singles from 12 to 14 February, the ice dance from 13 to 16 February, and the women's singles from 18 to 20 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The exhibition gala took place on 21 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Russia won five medals, including three gold and two silver.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Canada won one silver, with China and Germany each winning one bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] American figure skater Tara Lipinski became the youngest competitor in Winter Olympics history to earn a gold medal in an individual event.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Six short track speed skating events took place at the White Ring (arena) from 17 to 21 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] A total of 18 nations were representing among the skaters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] South Korea won six medals, including three gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Canada won four medals, including two gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Host Japan won one gold and one silver; and China won five silver and one bronze medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 14th ranked Japanese skater Takafumi Nishitani beat the Olympic record in the 500m semi-finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the final, he led from the start and won the gold medal with a time of 42.862 seconds.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian Marc Gagnon, who was in second place, fell with two laps remaining.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Chinese skater An Yulong won the silver with a time of 43.022, 0.5 seconds of the Japanese skater Hitoshi Uematsu.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 1000 meters, world record holder Marc Gagnon was disqualified for obstruction in the quarter-finals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Chinese skater Li Jiajun, who led for most of the final, was passed by the South Korean skater, Kim Dong-sung, in the final corner.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Kim won with a time of 1:32.375, 0.053 seconds ahead of the silver medalist.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian Éric Bédard won the bronze, .223 seconds further behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 5000m relays, world-title holders from Italy led at the beginning of the relay but were passed by the Canadians, and fell.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] With about one-quarter of the race left, a Chinese skater fell, bringing down with him a South Korean skater, allowing the Canadians to easily win the gold, with a time of 7:06.075.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The South Koreans were .701 seconds behind, with the Chinese finishing with the bronze a further 4 seconds back.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Japanese team won the B-Final with a time that was five seconds faster than the gold medalists.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the women's 500m final, the Canadian Isabelle Charest collided with the Chinese Wang Chunlu, and both fell.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Charest was disqualified and Wang, angry, never finished the race.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian Annie Perreault won the gold with a time of 46.568 seconds, 0.059 seconds ahead of Yang Yang (S) of China.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Because these were the only two to finish the race, the bronze medal went to the winner of the B-Final, the South Korean Chun Lee-kyung.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 1000m race, the Chinese skater Yang Yang (A) led the race but was passed by the 500m bronze medalist, Chun, in the last straight away to the finish line.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Chun won the race with a time of 1:42.776 seconds.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Yang Yang (A) was disqualified for using her elbow to try to block Chun.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Yang Yang (S) won the silver, 0.567 seconds behind the gold medalist from South Korea.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Won Hye-kyung, also of South Korea, won the bronze a further 0.18 seconds behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 3000m relay, the Chinese team led for most of the race but the South Korean skater Kim Yun-mi passed Yang Yang (A) in the last changeover.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Both teams beat the World Record, with the South Koreans finishing with a time of 4:16.260, and the Chinese were 0.123 seconds behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian team won bronze with a time of 4:21.205.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] From 8–20 February 171 athletes from 25 countries took part in the long-track speed skating events that were held in Nagano City at M-Wave, Japan's first indoor, long-track speed skating venue.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Netherlands won 11 medals, including five gold and four silver.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Canada, host Japan, and the USA also won multiple medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Twelve Olympic records and five World records were established at the Games on the ice at M-Wave.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Gianni Romme and Marianne Timmer, both of the Netherlands, each won two gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Nagano Olympics were the first where athletes wore clap skates.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] On the men's side, the world record holder in the men's 500m was the Japanese skater Hiroyasu Shimizu.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Shimizu was the smallest skater at the Games, 1.62m tall.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 500m was run over two races for the first time at these Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Shimizu was fastest in both races becoming only the second ever Japanese to win a singles title at the Olympic Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Finishing in second and third were the Canadian skaters, Jeremy Wotherspoon and Kevin Overland, who are 1.91m and 1.84 m tall, respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Shimizu's combined time was 1:11.35, 0.49 seconds ahead of Wotherspoon, and another 0.02 seconds ahead of Overland.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 1500m was won by Norwegian Ådne Søndrål with a world record time of 1:47.87.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Søndrål was 0.26 and 0.65 seconds ahead of two Dutch skaters, Ids Postma, and Rintje Ritsma.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 1000m, Postma won gold, with a time of 1:10.64, followed by another Dutch skater Jan Bos, who was 0.07 seconds behind, and Shimizu who won the bronze with a time of 1:11.00.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 5000m, the Dutch skater Gianni Romme won gold, with a world record time of 6:22.20, followed by Ritsma, who was 6.04 seconds behind, and Bart Veldkamp, representing Belgium who won the bronze with a time of 6:28.31.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Finally, in the 10,000m, three Dutch skaters won medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Romme won gold with a world record time, 15 seconds ahead of the world record, of 13:15.33, Bob de Jong won silver, and Ritsma won bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] On the women's side, the 500 m title was won by the Canadian Catriona Le May Doan, the favorite, who beat or equalled the world record four times before the Games.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Her teammate, Susan Auch, finished second.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Both were coached by Susan's brother, Derrick Auch.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Tomomi Okazaki, of host Japan, won the bronze medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 1500m, Dutch skater Marianne Timmer won gold with a world record time of 1:57.58.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German skater Gunda Niemann was second, 1.08 seconds behind, and the American skater Chris Witty won bronze with a time of 1:58.97.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 1000m, Timmer won gold again, with a time of 1:16.51.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Witty won silver, 0.26 seconds behind, and Le May Doan won bronze with a time of 1:17.37.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German skater Franziska Schenk, one of the favorites, fell during the second lap.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the 3000m, German skaters won all three medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Niemann won gold with a time of 4:07.29; Claudia Pechstein won silver, 1.18 seconds back; and Anni Friesinger won bronze with a time of 4:09.44.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Finally, in the 5000m, Pechstein won gold with a world record time of 6:59.61; Niemann was 0.04 seconds back for silver, and the Kazakh skater Lyudmila Prokasheva won bronze, with a time of 7:11.14.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Prokasheva's medal was the first medal by a female Kazakh athlete at any Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Alpine skiing events took place at Hakuba Happoone Winter Resort in Hakuba village, 50 kilometers west of Nagano City, and at Mount Higashidate in the Shiga Highlands in Yamanouchi, Nagano, 30 kilometers northeast of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 249 athletes, 141 males and 108 females, from 49 countries, took part in the 10 Alpine skiing events, men's and women's downhill, super-G, giant slalom, slalom, and combined.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Austria won 11 medals, including three gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Germany also won three gold, and six medals in total.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Seven other countries also won medals, including Australia, whose Zali Steggall won that countries first ever individual Winter Olympics medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The most successful athletes at these Games were Katja Seizinger from Germany, who won two gold medals and one bronze; and Hermann Maier, from Austria, who won two gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The cross-country skiing events took place at Nozawa Onsen Ski Resort, in the town of Nozawaonsen, approximately 50 kilometers north of Nagano.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 228 athletes, including 126 men and 102 women, from 37 countries took part.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Russia won eight medals, including all the women five gold medals, and Norway won nine medals, including four gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Six other countries also won medals, including Finland with one gold and two bronze, and Italy with two silver and two bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Larisa Lazutina from Russia won five medals, including three gold; and Bjørn Dæhlie from Norway won four medals, including three gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The freestyle skiing competition was held at the Iizuna Kogen Ski Area, 12 kilometers north of Nagano, from 8 to 18 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] It was the third consecutive Games that freestyle skiing events took place.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The four events, men's and women's moguls and aerials, involved 110 athletes from 25 countries .
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The United States won three gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Athletes from Finland won a silver and a bronze medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Six other countries took home either one silver or one bronze medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In men's moguls, the American Jonny Moseley was first after the qualifications.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Two cousins from Finland, Janne Lahtela and Sami Mustonen, who had never medalled at the FIS Freestyle Ski World Cup, were ranked second and third behind Moseley.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Moseley easily won the final with a score of 26.93.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Lahtela was .93 points behind, and Mustonen was another .24 points behind.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian, Jean-Luc Brassard, gold medalist from the 1994 Winter Olympics, finished in fourth.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In men's aerials, the American Eric Bergoust, who had fallen during training, overtook the other competitors with a score of 255.64 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Frenchmen, Sébastien Foucras, and the Belarusian, Dmitri Dashinski, were second and third.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian, Nicolas Fontaine, world champion in 1997, only managed 10th place after falling on his second jump.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Japanese moguls skier, Tae Satoya, 11th after qualifications, surprised everyone by winning the gold medal with a score of 25.06.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] She was the first female Japanese Olympic champion.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German, Tatjana Mittermayer scored 24.62 points and won the silver medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Norwegian, Kari Traa, won the bronze with a score of 24.09 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In women's aerials, American Nikki Stone won the gold medal with a score of 193.00 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The ex-gymnast, Xu Nannan from China won silver with a score of 186.97, and Colette Brand from Switzerland won bronze with a score of 171.83.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Nordic combined events were held at the Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium and the Snow Harp, both in Hakuba village, 50 kilometers west of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 53 athletes from 14 countries, took part in the two events, individual and team.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] France and Russia each won one of the bronze medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first event was the individual competition that took place on 13 and 14 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The silver medalist from the 1994 Winter Olympics, the Norwegian Bjarte Engen Vik, was the 1997–98 FIS Nordic Combined World Cup leader.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At the Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium, Vik led after the first two jumps.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] He was followed by the Russian Valeri Stoliarov.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The following day, the skiers left, in order of the placement following the ski jump, along te 15 kilometer cross-country race at the Snow Harp.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Vik led throughout and finished with a 27.5 second lead over second place.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] With three kilometers to the finish line, the Finnish athlete, 18-year-old Samppa Lajunen, who was sixth after the jumps, caught up with Stoliarov.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The skied together until the stadium, and 60 meters from the finish line, Lajunen passed the Russian and picked up the silver medal 0.7 seconds ahead of Stoliarov who won the bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The fastest athlete on the course was the Swiss skier, Marco Zarucchi, who was 43rd after the jumps, finished in 25th place.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Eleven nations took part in the team event on 19 and 20 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At previous Olympics, the team event involved three athletes per team, with the completing a 3x10 kilometer relay.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At Nagano, the team was enlarged to four athletes who completed a 4x5 kilometer relay.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] After the jumps, the team from Finland led by four seconds ahead of the Austrians, eight seconds ahead of the Norwegians, nine ahead of the Czechs, and 29 seconds ahead of the Japanese.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Norwegians quickly took the lead and never looked back.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The last Norwegian skier had the time to grab his country's flag with 500 meters from the finish line, and they won gold with more than one minute lead over the team from Finland.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The French team, sixth after the jumps, won the bronze medal ahead of the Austrians.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Japanese, gold medalists at the 1992 Winter Olympics and 1994 Winter Olympics finished in fifth.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The ski jumping competitions took place at the Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium in Hakuba village, 50 kilometers west of Nagano City.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 68 athletes from 19 countries participated.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] For the first time, the top 30 jumpers qualified for the second round.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Host Japan won the most medals, including two gold in the large hill and large hill team.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Finland, Germany, and Austria rounded out the medal table.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Kazuyoshi Funaki from Yoichi, Hokkaido in Japan won two gold and one silver for the host country.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The normal hill jumps took place on 11 February in front of 45,000 spectators.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Japanese, who had dominated the 1997–98 FIS Ski Jumping World Cup season, were the favorites.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] With a jump of 91.5 meters, Masahiko Harada led after the first round ahead of the Finnish jumper, Jani Soininen Kazuyoshi Funaki, who was fourth after the first round, took the lead with a jump of 90.5 meters in the second round.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] After a delay caused by strong wind, Soininen took the lead with only Harada still to jump.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] A sidewind blew when Harada jumped, and only managed 84.5 meters to finish in fifth place overall.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Soininen won gold with 234.5 points, Funaki was second with 233.5, and the Austrian Andreas Widhölzl finished third with 232.5 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] On 15 February, the large hill jump competition took place.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] 60,000 spectators gathered at Hakuba Ski Jumping Stadium.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Normal hill bronze medalist Widhölzl led after the first round, ahead of the Japanese jumper Takanobu Okabe, Jani Soininen et Funaki.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the second round, Funaki jumped 132.5 m, and, for the first time at the Olympics, received perfect points for his style.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] He jumped into first place and won the gold medal with 272.3 points overall.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] It was the first Japanese gold medal in ski jumping since the 1972 Winter Olympics in Sapporo.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Unfortunately, the measurement system was installed between 95 and 135 meters and his jump was beyond that.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] He was measured manually to be 136 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] He also had good points but only managed to win the bronze medal with 258.3. meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Soininen won the silver with a combined score of 260.8 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] At the 1994 Winter Olympics, the Japanese team were the favorites but Harada jumped poorly, costing the Japanese the gold medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Again, in 1998, the Japanese were the favorites.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The team event took place on 17 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The start was slowed by 30 minutes because of heavy falling snow.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The first two Japanese jumpers, Okabe at Hiroya Saitō, jumped Japan into first place.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Harada completely missed his jump, jumping only 79.5 meters, and despite Funaki having a good jump, Japan drop from first to fourth after the first round behind Austria, Germany, and Norway.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Okabe jumped 137 meters, which was an Olympic record.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Harada was next, and like Okabe, jumped 137 meters.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The last jumper was Funaki who jumped 125 meters, and the Japanese team became Olympic champions with 933.0 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Germans won silver with 897.4 points, and the Austrians finished with 881.5 points for the bronze.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the decade leading up the games, snowboarding had become popular in both North America and Europe, as well as Japan, and as a result, in August 1994, the NAOC received a request from the IOC president Samaranch to consider including snowboarding at the 1998 Winter Olympics.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] To reduce costs, NAOC asked the host community to cover a portion of the costs – the town Yamanouchi agreed – and FIS was expected to support financially as well.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In November 1995, the NAOC executive board agreed to add snowboarding, and this was approved by the IOC at their December meeting the following month in Karuizawa.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] This was the first Winter Olympics with snowboarding events.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The events took place at Mount Yakebitai and Kanbayashi Snowboard Park in Yamanouchi, Nagano, 30 kilometers northeast of Nagano City, from 8 to 12 February.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In all, 125 athletes from 22 countries participated in the men's and women's halfpipe and giant slalom.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Athletes from Germany won two medals, including one gold.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Athletes from Switzerland, France, and Canada also won gold medals.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the men's giant slalom, the Canadian Jasey-Jay Anderson won the first race with a half-second lead ahead of Rebagliati.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] During the second race, the event was temporary delayed because of snow and fog.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Ross Rebagliati finished with a combined time of 2:03.96, 0.02 seconds ahead of the Italian Thomas Prugger, and another 0.10 seconds ahead of the Swiss Ueli Kestenholz.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Controversy occurred when three days after the men's giant slalom, the International Olympic Committee determined that gold medalist Rebagliati from Canada, was disqualified after testing positive for marijuana.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] It was the first time in Olympic history that an athlete was disqualified for marijuana.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Canadian Olympic Committee lodged a protest and the case quickly went to the Court of Arbitration for Sport where it was ruled that because marijuana was not classified as a "banned" substance, the medal should be returned to the Canadian athlete.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the halfpipe, the gold medal went to the Swiss Gian Simmen, who had the highest score, 85.2, despite a heavy rain.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Norwegian Daniel Franck won the silver with a score of 82.4, and the American Ross Powers won the bronze with a score of 82.1.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The women's giant slalom was delayed one day because of a snowstorm.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The big favorite, the Frenchwoman Karine Ruby won the first race with almost two seconds ahead of her compatriot Isabelle Blanc.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Ruby won the second race, with Blanc missing the last gate and falling.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The German Heidi Renoth won the silver with a time of 2:19.17, and the Austrian Brigitte Köck won the bronze with a time of 2:19.42.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] In the halfpipe, the Norwegian Stine Brun Kjeldaas won the qualification round.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] However, in the finals, the German Nicola Thost, a former gymnast, finished second in both legs, scored 74.6 points, which was enough for the gold medal.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Stine Brun Kjeldaas finished fourth in the first leg and first in second, winning the silver with 74.2 points.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The American Shannon Dunn-Downing won the first leg, but finished seventh in the second leg, leaving her with the bronze with a score of 72.8.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The mascots of the 1998 Winter Olympics are four owls named Sukki, Nokki, Lekki and Tsukki, also known as the Snowlets.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Nagano Olympics were covered by more than 10,000 members of the media, including 8,329 accredited journalists, of which 2,586 were from newspaper media and 5,743 television and radio journalists.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Organizing Committee established a Main Press Center (MPC), over two buildings, and 17 annexes throughout the different sites.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The International Broadcast Centre (IBC) was a temporary one-storey facility constructed on the grounds of a former textile mill in the immediate vicinity of the MPC and Big Hat.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] A wide range of general services, such as a restaurants, cafeterias, banks, post offices and a medical clinics were available at the IBC.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The IBC was later converted into a departament store, *K's Town Wakasato Store*.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The MBC, which is today the *Wakasato Civic Cultural Center*, was built beside Big Hat, the main ice hockey venue.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The MBC had a surface area of 42,728 m2, with one principal room for 600 journalists of 1430m2 and another of 5100m2 that was rented by various press agencies.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The largest press offices at the Games were Kyodo News, Associated Press, Agence France-Presse, Reuters, and Deutsche Presse-Agentur.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The MBC also included a press conference room for 600 people.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The host broadcaster for the Games, the Olympic Radio and Televisions Organization (ORTO'98) was established as a separate organization within NAOC, the organizing committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] ORTO'98 was joint-venture created between NHK, the Japanese public broadcaster, the National Association of Broadcasters (NAB), and NAOC.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] A total of 1647 staff worked 386 cameras at the various venues and events, with coverage increasing by 55% over the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The Games were broadcast in 160 countries, 40 more than in Lillehammer, and it was estimated that 10.7 billion viewers watched the Games over the 16-day period.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Some events were filmed and broadcast in analog high-definition television, with NHK broadcasting over 270 hours of coverage in Japan.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] Broadcasting rights totaled USD$513 million, which was a record for the Winter Olympics, and all contracts with 16 broadcasting rights' holders were record sums.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] This money was split 60–40 between NAOC and the International Olympic Committee.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The American broadcasting network, CBS, paid 375 million US dollars, to air the Games in the United States.
[src:bleacher-report/1998-winter-olympics-p02] The 1998 Winter Olympics are the most recent Olympic Games to not air on NBC in the United States, as the current contract with NBC started in 1999.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The **2025 FIFA Club World Cup**, also marketed as **FIFA Club World Cup 25**, was the 21st edition of the FIFA Club World Cup, an international club soccer competition organized by FIFA.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] This was also the first edition under the new expanded format.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The tournament was held in the United States from June 14 to July 13, 2025, and featured 32 teams.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The expanded format included the continental champions from the past four years as well as additional qualified teams.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Chelsea won the tournament, defeating Paris Saint-Germain 3–0 in the final and becoming the inaugural world champions under the expanded format.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The revised structure was modeled more closely on the FIFA World Cup as a quadrennial world championship, replacing the annual seven-team format used between 2000 and 2023.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] It featured the winners of each continent's top club competition from 2021 to 2024, except for a single entry from Oceania.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Additional slots were awarded to clubs from Europe and South America based on rankings across the same four-year period.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Manchester City, who won the final edition under the previous format in 2023, entered as the technical title holders but were eliminated in the round of 16 by Al Hilal.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] FIFA first announced the expanded format in March 2019, originally selecting China to host the inaugural edition in 2021.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] This was later postponed due to the global COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] In February 2023, FIFA confirmed the allocation of qualification slots among confederations, and four months later announced the United States as the new host nation.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Alongside this expansion, FIFA also introduced the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, an annual tournament based on the previous Club World Cup format.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The expansion of the tournament drew varied responses, with some concerns raised by the players' union FIFPRO and the World Leagues Forum regarding potential effects on fixture schedules and player welfare.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Ticket sales were managed using dynamic pricing, which was later adjusted for several matches to boost attendance.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] International broadcasting rights were secured by streaming service DAZN, which sublicensed coverage to other networks.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] A total of $1 billion in prize money was distributed among the 32 clubs, including solidarity payments and allocations by confederation.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] It was the first major FIFA tournament since the 1978 FIFA World Cup not to feature a penalty shootout.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Since its return from hiatus in 2005, the FIFA Club World Cup had been held annually in December and was limited to the winners of continental club competitions.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] As early as late 2016, FIFA president Gianni Infantino suggested expanding the Club World Cup to 32 teams beginning in 2019 and rescheduling it to June/July to be more balanced and attractive to broadcasters and sponsors.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] In late 2017, FIFA discussed proposals to expand the competition to 24 teams and have it be played every four years starting in 2021, replacing the FIFA Confederations Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The expanded format and schedule of Club World Cup, to be played in June and July 2021, was confirmed at the March 2019 FIFA Council meeting in Miami.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] China was appointed as host in October 2019, but the 2021 event was canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] On June 23, 2023, FIFA confirmed that the United States would host the 2025 tournament as a prelude to the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The 32 teams were divided into eight groups of four teams, with the top two teams in each group qualifying to the knockout stage.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] However, the only difference from the format used in the FIFA World Cup between 1998 and 2022 was that there was no third place playoff.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] FIFA unveiled a newly designed trophy created by Tiffany & Co. for the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Made from pure 24-karat gold, the trophy's design drew inspiration from pioneering maps, the periodic table, astronomy, and the Voyager Golden Record.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] It featured laser-engraved details including a world map, the names of all 211 FIFA member associations, descriptions of football, and inscriptions in 13 languages, including braille.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The trophy weighs approximately 5 kilograms (11 lb) and is valued between €200,000 or US$230,000.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The original trophy was kept by United States president Donald Trump in the Oval Office, while an identical replica was awarded to Chelsea, the first winners of the expanded tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] On February 14, 2023, the FIFA Council approved the slot allocation for the 2025 tournament based on a "set of objective metrics and criteria".
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] UEFA was awarded the most slots with twelve, while CONMEBOL was given the second most with six.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The AFC, CAF, and CONCACAF were all given four slots, while the OFC and the host association were given one slot each.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] On March 14, 2023, the FIFA Council approved the key principles of the access list for the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] If a club won two or more seasons of its confederation's top club competition, additional teams determined club rankings over the four-year period.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Furthermore, a restriction of two clubs per association was applied, with the exception of champion clubs if more than two clubs from the same association won their confederation's top club competition.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The calculation method for the four-year club rankings within each confederation was based on the teams' performance in their respective continental tournaments during seasons completed between 2021 and 2024.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] In the case of UEFA, due to the existence of the well-established UEFA club coefficient system, the method used by UEFA to calculate the club coefficient was "exceptionally applied" to rank the European teams.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The draw was held on December 5, 2024, 1:00 p.m.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] EST, at the headquarters of television broadcaster Telemundo in the Miami suburb of Doral, Florida.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was led by Alessandro Del Piero at the Telemundo headquarters.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] FIFA announced the draw procedure and seeding pots two days prior to the draw, taking into consideration sporting and geographical factors as far as possible.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] In the draw, teams from the same confederation could not be drawn into the same group except for UEFA teams, for which there was at least one and no more than two per group.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Additionally, teams from the same national association could be drawn into the same group.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] To maintain competitive balance, two separate pathways of four groups were established for the knockout stage.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] As teams from the host country and for scheduling purposes, Inter Miami and the Seattle Sounders were drawn into position 4 of Groups A and B, respectively.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Consequently, teams drawn into Groups A and B were allocated to the position corresponding to their draw pot.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The draw started with Pot 1 and ended with Pot 4, with each team selected then allocated into the first available group alphabetically, based on the draw constraints.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] For Groups C to H, the position for the team within the group was then drawn (for the purpose of the match schedule), with the Pot 1 teams automatically drawn into position 1 of each group.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Lumen Field hosted all three group stage matches for the Seattle Sounders.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Of these selected stadiums, five will be used in the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Contrary to other FIFA tournaments, including the upcoming 2026 FIFA World Cup, all venues kept their original naming rights.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] According to a report from *The Athletic*, FIFA designated sites in host cities for team training bases, with priority given to clubs that had more matches in the area.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Clubs were permitted to independently negotiate with other facility owners and operators, including several college athletic programs, to secure their own base.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Several facilities were also designated by FIFA for use later in the tournament by qualified teams in the knockout rounds.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The team base camps for the group stage were confirmed by FIFA on June 3, 2025.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] On April 14, 2025, FIFA confirmed that 117 match officials from 41 member associations would be selected for the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] This included 35 referees, 58 assistant referees, and 24 video match officials.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] On December 17, 2023, FIFA announced the tournament would take place from June 15 to July 13, 2025.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Prior to the draw, only the date and venue of the opening match (involving Inter Miami) and final was confirmed, along with the venue for the group stage matches of the Seattle Sounders.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The full match schedule with venues and kickoff times was finalized and published on December 7, 2024, following the draw.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The start date of the tournament was altered, with the tournament beginning one day earlier on June 14.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] The schedule was created taking into account factors such as "sporting and player-centric criteria, local and traveling fans and global broadcast considerations".
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Each club was required to name a provisional squad of between 26 and 50 players for the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] From June 1 to 10, 2025, the member associations of all participating clubs implemented an extraordinary transfer window to allow for the registration of newly signed players.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Clubs were required to name their final squads of between 26 and 35 players, including at least three goalkeepers, by June 10.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] During the competition, clubs could make limited changes to their final lists from June 27 to July 3, should the club's member association have a transfer window open during this period, though no player could appear for two clubs during the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Should a club's goalkeeper have suffered from an injury or illness, that player could be replaced at any time.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] French Montana and Swae Lee headlined the opening ceremony, which took place at Miami's Hard Rock Stadium before the opening match between Al Ahly and Inter Miami.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Singers Vikina and Richaelio also performed during the ceremony, which was broadcast on DAZN.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] In the group stage, teams were divided into eight groups of four (groups A to H).
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Teams in each group played one another in a round-robin, from which the top two teams advanced to the knockout stage.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Tied on head-to-head result (Porto 4–4 Al Ahly).
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p01] Overall goal difference was used as the tiebreaker.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In the knockout stage, if the scores were equal when normal playing time expired, extra time was played for two periods of 15 minutes each.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] This was followed, if required, by a penalty shootout to determine the winners.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The following awards were given at the conclusion of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] FIFA also named a man of the match for the best player in each game at the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] For sponsorship reasons, this was known as the "Michelob Ultra Superior Player of the Match" award.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Additionally, FIFA also shortlisted ten goals for the goal of the tournament award, which Lucas Ribeiro of Mamelodi Sundowns won for his goal against Borussia Dortmund, beating the likes of Lionel Messi's free kick against Porto, Kenan Yıldız against Al Ain and João Pedro against Fluminense.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The distribution model split a total prize pool of US$1 billion between the 32 participating clubs.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The winner of the tournament was awarded up to US$125 million, marking a significant increase in financial rewards compared to previous editions.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In addition to the prize money for the participating teams, a solidarity investment program had a target of an additional US$250 million being provided to club football across the world.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In July 2024, FIFA opened bids for media rights to the Club World Cup in the Americas, Asia, the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On September 19, 2024, FIFA called an emergency meeting to discuss broadcasting rights, as it had not yet reached deals in a number of major markets.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On December 4, 2024, DAZN acquired global rights to the tournament for €1 billion, streaming all matches for free.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] DAZN would also collaborate with Host Broadcasting Services (HBS) on aspects of the world feed production.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In some regions, DAZN sublicensed coverage to linear television broadcasters.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In the United States, DAZN reached sub-licensing and co-production agreements with Warner Bros.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Discovery's TNT Sports (English) and TelevisaUnivision's TUDN (Spanish), under which their respective properties would hold exclusive rights to portions of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The two divisions would co-produce studio programming for the tournament seen across their properties and DAZN, with TNT Sports originating English-language coverage from its studios in Atlanta.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Media reports suggested that DAZN struggled to find a buyer in the UK, as the BBC was unwilling to sublicense for fear of promoting a commercial broadcaster, and ITV had attempted to obtain the rights for free before the deal was signed with DAZN.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The rights were eventually sublicensed to 5, which enjoyed strong ratings in the 16–34 demographic.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On April 10, 2025, Chinese streaming platform Migu acquired broadcast rights in China to the 2025 and 2029 Club World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Since DAZN does not operate in China, it was understood that FIFA negotiated the deal with Migu directly in partnership with the Chinese Football Association.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On June 11, 2025, Coupang Play in South Korea announced it would provide coverage of the FIFA Club World Cup under a separate pricing plan to its basic plan.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In the days prior to the tournament, Sportradar announced agreements to serve as the exclusive provider of real-time sports betting data for the tournament, expanding upon existing agreements with FIFA to provide match integrity services.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The agreement also included non-exclusive rights to distribute DAZN's coverage of the tournament via sports betting platforms.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On September 4, 2024, FIFA released the official emblem and audio signature of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The emblem took inspiration from the ball, football history and culture, with the initials of the tournament abstracted into a circular icon.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The official audio featured Italian singer Gala's song "Freed from Desire".
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On November 14, FIFA unveiled the new Club World Cup trophy.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On January 29, 2025, it was announced that FIFA Music Ambassador Robbie Williams would perform at the tournament, including a new song.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On January 31, 2025, the official match ball was revealed by Adidas.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The design featured jagged-edged block patterns and deconstructed stars and stripes in red, white, and blue, the colors of the flag of the United States.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On July 7, the official match ball for the final was revealed.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] It featured the same design as the previous ball, but the red part was switched to gold.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The ball was used for the tournament's last three matches: both semi-finals and the final, all of which were held at the MetLife Stadium in East Rutherford.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Alongside Gala's "Freed from Desire", a remake of the Queen song "We Will Rock You" by American rapper Pitbull and producer RedOne served as one of the official songs of the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Pitbull sang the 2014 FIFA World Cup official song, "We Are One (Ole Ola)", while RedOne produced the 2022 tournament's official album.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The TV title sequence used a remix of "Freed from Desire" released by Diplo the previous year.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] La Liga also voiced opposition and threatened legal action.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Critics accused FIFA of prioritising commercial interests over player health.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The introduction of the annual FIFA Intercontinental Cup was similarly criticised.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In May 2024, FIFPRO and the World Leagues Forum sent a letter to FIFA demanding rescheduling and reform of the FIFA International Match Calendar and warned of legal or other action if their concerns were ignored.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On June 13, 2024, the English Professional Footballers' Association and France's Union Nationale des Footballeurs Professionnels filed a legal claim in the Business Court in Brussels to protest the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] FIFPRO also warned of potential strike action.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On January 30, 2025, a meeting between FIFA and FIFPRO was held to address fixture congestion.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In response to the criticism, FIFA stated that the Club World Cup's schedule followed the international calendar and allowed for rest before domestic competitions, adding that its events occupied just 1 percent of the football calendar and were agreed with players and confederations.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Several clubs in the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup were linked to multi-club ownership structures, raising concerns about conflicts of interest.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Among them were Mexican sides Pachuca and León, both owned by Grupo Pachuca.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] FIFA regulations prohibit any club from owning shares in, being a member of, or exerting influence over another participating club, with "influence" defined through control of voting rights or decision-making authority.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In November 2024, Costa Rican club Alajuelense requested FIFA to apply this rule and disqualify one of the two Grupo Pachuca clubs, threatening legal action if no action was taken.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Alajuelense argued that it was next in line to qualify under CONCACAF's rankings, but FIFA determined the club could not be party to proceedings.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On February 4, 2025, Alajuelense appealed to the Court of Arbitration for Sport against FIFA, Pachuca, and León.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On March 21, FIFA announced that León had been removed from the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] According to *The Guardian*, a play-off would determine the replacement between Los Angeles FC, runner-up of the 2023 CONCACAF Champions League, and América, the highest-ranked Mexican club not already qualified.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Alajuelense and the Philadelphia Union were not considered.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] León appealed, and hearings for both its case and Alajuelense's took place in April and May 2025 respectively, but on May 6 FIFA confirmed that León's expulsion would stand and that the play-off would proceed.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] LAFC secured the final spot with a 2–1 extra time win over América on May 31 at BMO Stadium.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] A 10 percent cancellation fee applied to exchanges also drew attention, but the overall response to the tournament was positive.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The opening fixture between Al Ahly and Inter Miami saw strong turnout following final-week promotional campaigns, and FIFA reported over 60,000 spectators in attendance, with strong international broadcast figures.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] By early July, FIFA had recorded over 2 million tickets sold and average attendance of approximately 36,000 per match, a figure comparable to several leading European domestic leagues.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] While 14 matches attracted smaller crowds of under 20,000, mostly at MLS venues, 11 fixtures surpassed 90 percent capacity, including six at Hard Rock Stadium.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Supporters from South America, Africa and Asia were especially prominent throughout the tournament, although a match involving Wydad and Juventus saw minor incidents involving smoke bombs and one arrest.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] As with previous editions of the FIFA Club World Cup, the expanded 2025 format allocated a slot for the host nation.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] This slot had traditionally been filled by the domestic league champion of the host country.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In the United States, the champion of Major League Soccer is determined through the MLS Cup playoffs, rather than regular season performance, and for the 2024 season, that playoff had not yet concluded at the time FIFA needed to confirm its selection.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] During the mid-season 2024 MLS All-Star Game, MLS Commissioner Don Garber stated that the slot could be awarded to the 2024 MLS Supporters' Shield winner, the MLS Cup 2024 winner, or via a playoff between the two.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On October 19, 2024, FIFA announced that Inter Miami would represent the host nation as winners of the Supporters' Shield, awarding the slot before the start of the 2024 MLS Cup playoffs and after Inter Miami had already secured the Shield.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] FIFA stated that this decision aligned with past precedent, where clubs that won silverware in a league-style format were prioritised for the host slot, and that the announcement had been delayed due to procedural timelines for confirming regulations.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Although the decision drew scrutiny from some sections of the media and fanbase, particularly regarding its timing and the involvement of Lionel Messi, others viewed it as a practical resolution in keeping with the tournament's structure and historical practice.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Inter Miami were later eliminated from the playoffs by Atlanta United in the first round on November 10, but head coach Gerardo Martino defended the club's inclusion on the grounds that the Supporters' Shield constituted a valid and recognised form of domestic achievement.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] On June 10, 2025, Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) and Customs and Border Protection (CBP) announced their involvement in providing security during the first round of the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup and reminded non-American citizens to carry valid proof of legal stay.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The announcement raised concerns among some fans regarding the Trump administration's deportation policy, especially as those detained could potentially face indefinite detention or be transferred to other "third countries", such as El Salvador.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] FIFA President Gianni Infantino defended the increased security presence, stating that the safety of fans was a top priority, particularly in light of the 2024 Copa América final, which was held in the same stadium and saw large numbers of supporters storm the gates to gain entry.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Just days later, on June 15, reports surfaced that Boca Juniors defender Ayrton Costa had initially been denied a US visa due to a 2018 robbery case, although the decision was subsequently reversed and he was issued a special 26-day visa to participate in the tournament.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The tournament intensified the rivalry between European teams and the rest of the world, in particular the South Americans.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Initially the debate involved how well the non-European teams would fare against the European teams; it then intensified when South American teams began to record victories against their European counterparts.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Some South American managers, fans, and journalists also tried to dismiss European criticism of the tournament as "loser excuses" and a "symbol of European arrogance and elitism".
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Commentators questioned whether European dominance had been overstated, with analysis suggesting that the myth of superiority was being tested by results on the pitch.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] In response, Paris Saint-Germain coach Luis Enrique remarked that South Americans had no need to compare themselves with Europeans, emphasising the shared global stature of both footballing regions and pointing to the widespread recruitment of South American players by European clubs.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Manchester City manager Pep Guardiola offered a more supportive view of South American competitiveness, arguing that European fans should not be surprised when clubs from the region secure wins and that such outcomes reflect the real global balance of quality in football.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] However, Chelsea coach Enzo Maresca argued that European clubs faced congested schedules that could affect player fitness, but a journalist noted that South American teams played even more matches during the same period, challenging the idea that European sides were uniquely overworked.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The increased attention to Brazilian clubs also led to a sharp spike in global interest in the Brazilian League, with Google Trends reporting the highest search volume for the term since 2020.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] While the performances reignited continental pride, the on-field results remained competitive; in twelve direct UEFA–CONMEBOL encounters, European clubs registered six wins, South American clubs won three times, and three matches ended in draws.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] The tournament was marked by significant weather-related and logistical disruptions, raising concerns ahead of the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Several matches were delayed or temporarily suspended due to thunderstorms and lightning, with stoppages ranging from around 46 minutes to nearly two hours, as FIFA safety protocols required repeated pauses whenever lightning was detected near stadiums.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] High temperatures also posed a challenge, particularly for midday kickoffs, with players and coaches highlighting the physical toll of extreme heat and uneven playing conditions between day and evening matches.
[src:bleacher-report/2025-fifa-club-world-cup-p02] Beyond the pitch, severe weather contributed to travel and traffic problems, including flight delays and congestion around venues, affecting teams, officials, media, and supporters, further intensifying debate about scheduling and infrastructure preparedness for future tournaments.
[src:bleacher-report/aew-all-access] This program initially aired on TBS in the United States, but upon AEW's announcement of expanding its relationship with Warner Bros.
[src:bleacher-report/aew-all-access] Discovery, *All Access* moved to the Max streaming service (formerly HBO Max) beginning on June 9, 2023.
[src:bleacher-report/aew-all-access] The series offers an all-access look into the backstage world of All Elite Wrestling.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In August 2011, the company announced a $22 million growth round led by Oak Investment Partners, with participation from Crosslink and Hillsven.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] At the time, Oak general partner Fred Harman, a board member at both *The Huffington Post* and Demand Media, characterized the investment as a bet on *Bleacher Report*'s ability to keep pace with real-time fan interest across all forms of social media.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] This continued under Turner ownership, as Turner had once owned World Championship Wrestling.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] Nemetz continued with the company for eight months after the acquisition, going on to advise and invest in other media platforms including *Elite Daily* and *Bustle*.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] As part of the integration process, Atherton's CFO responsibilities were assumed by Turner corporate in February 2013, and Grey stepped down from the CEO position in October 2013.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] After Grey's departure, Finocchio headed *Bleacher Report*, reporting to Turner Sports Chief Operating Officer, Matt Hong, up until September 2014.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In May 2014, Bleacher Report launched *Game of Zones*, a parody of HBO's *Game of Thrones* featuring animated NBA figures.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In September 2014, *Bleacher Report* named Dorth Raphaely General Manager, taking over for Finocchio, following his departure as CEO.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In 2015, *Bleacher Report* acquired the popular sports-themed Instagram page House of Highlights.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In January 2016, Finocchio returned to *Bleacher Report* as CEO.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In October 2016, *Bleacher Report* launched *Gridiron Heights*, a cartoon web series featuring satirical portrayals of NFL stars and executives.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In February 2017, the company announced that it was laying off over 50 employees, as the site stepped away from its open content model.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In July 2017, *Bleacher Report* announced that it named Howard Mittman as chief revenue officer and chief marketing officer.
[src:bleacher-report/bleacher-report] In September 2018, *Bleacher Report* launched the first episode of *The Champions*, an animated show involving the current Champions League members of that season.
